133
00:06:53,983 --> 00:06:55,792
(LOUD MUSIC PLAYING)

134
00:07:11,623 --> 00:07:12,954
Hey, Scotty. What's up?

135
00:07:13,503 --> 00:07:15,232
I thought you were
supposed to be at work.

136
00:07:15,303 --> 00:07:17,146
I was. I got fired.

137
00:07:17,223 --> 00:07:18,952
Damn. They find out who you are?

138
00:07:19,023 --> 00:07:20,070
Yeah.

139
00:07:20,143 --> 00:07:21,872
LUIS: Baskin-Robbins
always finds out, bro.

140
00:07:21,943 --> 00:07:23,866
(SCOFFS) Baskin-Robbins don't play.

141
00:07:23,983 --> 00:07:27,192
- You want some waffles?
- Yeah, I'll take a waffle.

142
00:07:27,303 --> 00:07:28,714
Oh. That's Kurt.

143
00:07:28,783 --> 00:07:31,103
He was Folsom for five years.
He's a wizard on that laptop.

144
00:07:32,063 --> 00:07:34,464
- Nice meet you.
- Yeah. Nice to meet you, too.

145
00:07:35,343 --> 00:07:36,390
Who are you?

146
00:07:36,823 --> 00:07:37,824
Dave.

147
00:07:39,143 --> 00:07:40,713
Nice work on the Vista job.

148
00:07:41,663 --> 00:07:42,949
Vista job, yes.

149
00:07:43,023 --> 00:07:45,503
No, no. I have heard of this robbery.

150
00:07:45,583 --> 00:07:48,951
Well, technically, I didn't rob them.
Robbery involves threat.

151
00:07:49,023 --> 00:07:51,754
I hate violence. I burgled them.
I'm a cat burglar.

152
00:07:51,823 --> 00:07:53,268
You mean you're a pussy.

153
00:07:53,343 --> 00:07:54,424
Yeah.

154
00:07:54,503 --> 00:07:56,346
They were overcharging
the customers, right?

155
00:07:56,423 --> 00:07:57,868
And it added up to millions.

156
00:07:57,943 --> 00:07:59,832
He blows the whistle and he gets fired.

157
00:08:00,383 --> 00:08:01,669
And what does he do?

158
00:08:01,743 --> 00:08:03,666
He hacks into the security system

159
00:08:03,743 --> 00:08:06,428
and transfers millions
back to the people that they stole it from.

160
00:08:06,503 --> 00:08:08,426
- Posts all the bank records online.
- (WHISTLES)

161
00:08:08,503 --> 00:08:10,663
And he drove the dude's Bentley
into his swimming pool.

162
00:08:13,343 --> 00:08:15,152
What are you doing?

163
00:08:15,223 --> 00:08:16,270
Hmm?

164
00:08:17,103 --> 00:08:19,344
Why are you telling my life story
to these guys?

165
00:08:19,423 --> 00:08:20,709
What do you want?

166
00:08:20,783 --> 00:08:21,784
LUIS: Okay.

167
00:08:21,863 --> 00:08:24,264
My cousin talked to this guy
two weeks ago

168
00:08:24,343 --> 00:08:26,630
- about this little perfect job.
- No way.

169
00:08:26,703 --> 00:08:29,104
No, no, no. Wait!
This guy... This guy fits your M.O.

170
00:08:29,183 --> 00:08:30,183
No!

171
00:08:30,223 --> 00:08:32,544
I'm finished, man.
I'm not going back to jail.

172
00:08:32,623 --> 00:08:34,671
It's some retired millionaire
living off his golden parachute.

173
00:08:34,743 --> 00:08:36,711
It's a perfect Scott Lang mark!

174
00:08:36,783 --> 00:08:38,865
I don't care. I'm out.

175
00:08:57,623 --> 00:08:58,954
Dr. Pym?

176
00:08:59,023 --> 00:09:01,424
Yes. I'm still alive.

177
00:09:08,503 --> 00:09:09,550
ID?

178
00:09:11,103 --> 00:09:13,071
HANK: Perhaps that will suffice.

179
00:09:15,223 --> 00:09:17,305
Very sorry, sir. Please come in.

180
00:09:19,623 --> 00:09:21,591
(SOFTLY) Is that Hank Pym?

181
00:09:25,663 --> 00:09:26,949
Good morning, Hank.

182
00:09:28,223 --> 00:09:29,224
Hope.

183
00:09:29,303 --> 00:09:31,783
Would it kill you to call me Dad?

184
00:09:32,623 --> 00:09:35,627
Dr. Cross will be so pleased that
you could find the time to join us today.

185
00:09:36,143 --> 00:09:38,111
More like "thrilled."

186
00:09:38,903 --> 00:09:42,703
I was surprised to receive
any kind of invitation from you, Darren.

187
00:09:42,783 --> 00:09:44,194
What's the occasion?

188
00:09:44,263 --> 00:09:46,152
Oh, you'll see. Won't he, Hope?

189
00:09:50,663 --> 00:09:52,347
We're ready for you inside.

190
00:09:53,383 --> 00:09:54,544
Ouch.

191
00:09:55,623 --> 00:09:59,070
I guess some old wounds
never heal, huh?

192
00:09:59,143 --> 00:10:00,827
Don't worry, she's in good hands.

193
00:10:00,943 --> 00:10:02,069
(BEEPS)

194
00:10:02,623 --> 00:10:04,785
You're in for a treat.

195
00:10:07,303 --> 00:10:11,228
Long time, no see, Dr. Pym.
How's retirement?

196
00:10:11,863 --> 00:10:13,467
How's your face?

197
00:10:16,463 --> 00:10:18,272
After you.

198
00:10:25,863 --> 00:10:29,072
Now, before we start,
I'd like to introduce a very special guest.

199
00:10:29,143 --> 00:10:31,509
This company's founder and my mentor,

200
00:10:32,182 --> 00:10:33,183
Dr. Hank Pym.

201
00:10:48,822 --> 00:10:50,790
When I took over this company
for Dr. Pym,

202
00:10:50,862 --> 00:10:53,103
I immediately started
researching a particle

203
00:10:53,182 --> 00:10:55,947
that could change
the distance between atoms,

204
00:10:56,022 --> 00:10:58,866
while increasing density and strength.

205
00:10:59,342 --> 00:11:02,425
Why this revolutionary idea
remained buried

206
00:11:02,502 --> 00:11:06,791
beneath the dust and cobwebs of
Hank's research, I couldn't tell you.

207
00:11:06,862 --> 00:11:08,785
But just imagine,

208
00:11:08,862 --> 00:11:13,106
a soldier the size of an insect.

209
00:11:16,622 --> 00:11:18,112
The ultimate secret weapon.

210
00:11:19,222 --> 00:11:20,508
(YELLING)

211
00:11:30,102 --> 00:11:32,104
An Ant-Man.

212
00:11:32,222 --> 00:11:33,383
(CHUCKLES)

213
00:11:33,462 --> 00:11:35,430
That's what they called you.
Right, Hank?

214
00:11:39,782 --> 00:11:41,227
Silly, I know.

215
00:11:41,302 --> 00:11:42,792
Propaganda.

216
00:11:43,222 --> 00:11:44,951
Tales to astonish!

217
