<i>offers the user unlimited influence
to carry out protective actions.</i>

253
00:13:42,382 --> 00:13:45,113
<i>And, one day soon,
an army of Yellowjackets</i>

254
00:13:45,182 --> 00:13:50,393
<i>will create a sustainable environment
of well-being around the world.</i>

255
00:13:50,462 --> 00:13:52,351
<i>The Yellowjacket.</i>

256
00:13:53,222 --> 00:13:54,792
So, it's a suit?

257
00:13:54,862 --> 00:13:56,785
(PEOPLE
MURMURING INDISTINCTLY)

258
00:13:58,222 --> 00:13:59,951
Don't be crude, Frank.

259
00:14:00,022 --> 00:14:03,151
It's not a suit, it's a vessel.

260
00:14:03,782 --> 00:14:05,113
What's the matter?
You're not impressed?

261
00:14:05,182 --> 00:14:08,072
No, I'm impressed. I'm also concerned.

262
00:14:08,142 --> 00:14:11,112
Imagine what our enemies
could do with this tech.

263
00:14:11,222 --> 00:14:13,793
We should have a longer conversation
about that, Frank.

264
00:14:13,862 --> 00:14:15,626
I really value your opinion.

265
00:14:16,542 --> 00:14:18,146
Thank you for coming. Hope?

266
00:14:19,022 --> 00:14:21,593
Thank you very much, everybody.
I will escort you out now.

267
00:14:21,662 --> 00:14:22,788
Thank you.

268
00:14:26,102 --> 00:14:27,627
You seem a bit shocked.

269
00:14:27,702 --> 00:14:31,991
Darren, there's a reason
that I buried these secrets.

270
00:14:32,062 --> 00:14:34,064
(SOFTLY) So you finally admit it!

271
00:14:34,822 --> 00:14:38,349
We could have done this together, Hank.
But you ruined that.

272
00:14:39,182 --> 00:14:40,627
That's why you're the past
and I'm the future.

273
00:14:40,702 --> 00:14:43,148
Don't do this.

274
00:14:43,702 --> 00:14:45,386
MITCHELL: Dr. Cross?

275
00:14:46,622 --> 00:14:49,387
You sell to me first,
20% over your asking price,

276
00:14:49,462 --> 00:14:51,351
I can have the cash here in two weeks.

277
00:14:51,422 --> 00:14:52,628
DARREN: Deal.

278
00:14:52,902 --> 00:14:54,586
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

279
00:15:01,302 --> 00:15:03,509
HOPE: We have to
make our move, Hank.

280
00:15:03,582 --> 00:15:04,629
How close is he?

281
00:15:04,702 --> 00:15:07,387
He still can't shrink a live subject.

282
00:15:07,462 --> 00:15:10,033
Just give me the suit and let me
finish this once and for all.

283
00:15:10,102 --> 00:15:11,103
No.

284
00:15:11,422 --> 00:15:13,231
I have Cross' complete trust.

285
00:15:13,302 --> 00:15:15,464
- It's too dangerous.
- We don't have a choice.

286
00:15:16,022 --> 00:15:18,104
Well, that's not entirely true.

287
00:15:20,102 --> 00:15:21,945
I think I found a guy.

288
00:15:23,422 --> 00:15:24,787
Who?

289
00:15:25,102 --> 00:15:27,184
- (MERRY MUSIC PLAYING)
- (CHILDREN SHRIEKING)

290
00:15:29,102 --> 00:15:30,592
Daddy!

291
00:15:30,662 --> 00:15:32,152
Peanut! Oh!

292
00:15:32,262 --> 00:15:34,424
Happy birthday!

293
00:15:34,502 --> 00:15:35,503
I'm so sorry I'm late.

294
00:15:35,582 --> 00:15:37,186
I didn't know
what time your party started.

295
00:15:37,262 --> 00:15:38,752
It was on the invitation.

296
00:15:38,822 --> 00:15:40,586
He didn't get an invitation.

297
00:15:40,662 --> 00:15:42,187
But he came anyway!

298
00:15:42,262 --> 00:15:45,232
Well, I'm not gonna miss
my little girl's birthday party.

299
00:15:45,302 --> 00:15:47,066
I'm gonna go tell Mommy you're here.

300
00:15:47,142 --> 00:15:48,143
Oh, you don't...

301
00:15:48,222 --> 00:15:49,223
What are you doing here, Lang?

302
00:15:49,302 --> 00:15:50,827
You haven't paid a dime of child support.

303
00:15:50,902 --> 00:15:52,586
You know, right now, if I wanted to,
I could arrest you.

304
00:15:52,662 --> 00:15:53,743
It's good to see you too, Paxton.

305
00:15:53,822 --> 00:15:57,144
Mommy's so happy you're here,
she choked on her drink.

306
00:15:57,222 --> 00:15:58,508
(CASSIE GIGGLES)

307
00:15:58,662 --> 00:16:01,393
Hey, look what I have for you.

308
00:16:01,462 --> 00:16:02,873
Can I open it now?

309
00:16:02,942 --> 00:16:04,671
Of course, sweetheart.
It's your birthday.

310
00:16:08,982 --> 00:16:10,632
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>You're my bestest friend.</i>

311
00:16:10,702 --> 00:16:11,863
(SOFTLY) What is that thing?

312
00:16:11,942 --> 00:16:13,671
He's so ugly!

313
00:16:14,142 --> 00:16:16,224
I love him!

314
00:16:16,302 --> 00:16:17,827
Can I go show my friends?

315
00:16:17,902 --> 00:16:19,825
Of course, sweetheart. Go ahead.

316
00:16:20,502 --> 00:16:22,142
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>You're my bestest friend.</i>

317
00:16:22,182 --> 00:16:24,310
Look, the child support
is coming, all right?

318
00:16:24,382 --> 00:16:26,422
It's just hard finding a job
when you have a record.

319
00:16:26,462 --> 00:16:29,262
I'm sure you'll figure it out.
But for now, I want you out of my house.

320
00:16:29,302 --> 00:16:30,792
- No way! It's my daughter's birthday.
- It's my house!

321
00:16:30,902 --> 00:16:32,462
- So what? It's my kid!
- MAGGIE: Scott!

322
00:16:33,462 --> 00:16:35,829
You can't just show up here.
You know that. Come on.

323
00:16:35,902 --> 00:16:36,949
It's a birthday party.

324
00:16:37,022 --> 00:16:38,706
Yeah, I know, but you can't just show up.

325
00:16:38,782 --> 00:16:39,783
She's my daughter.

326
00:16:39,862 --> 00:16:41,273
You don't know the first thing
about being a father.

327
00:16:41,342 --> 00:16:45,427
Maggie, I tell you this as a friend,
and as the first love of my life.

328
00:16:45,542 --> 00:16:47,465
Your fiancé is an asshat.

329
00:16:47,542 --> 00:16:48,623
He's not an asshat.

330
00:16:48,702 --> 00:16:51,592
- Hey, watch your language. Okay?
- What language? I said "hat."

331
00:16:51,662 --> 00:16:53,027
MAGGIE: Stop it.

332
00:16:54,302 --> 00:16:56,350
Really, Maggie? That guy?

333
00:16:56,422 --> 00:16:58,026
Come on!
You could marry anyone you want,

334
00:16:58,102 --> 00:16:59,467
and you have to get engaged to a cop?

335
00:16:59,542 --> 00:17:01,192
At least he's not a crook.

336
00:17:02,942 --> 00:17:05,786
I'm trying, okay? I've changed.
I'm straight.

337
00:17:05,862 --> 00:17:08,229
I had a job and...

338
00:17:09,742 --> 00:17:10,789
I wanna provide.

339
00:17:10,902 --> 00:17:13,428
I had a lot of time to think about it
and I love her.

340
00:17:13,502 --> 00:17:14,503
So much.

341
00:17:14,582 --> 00:17:17,904
I've missed so much time
and I wanna be a part of her life.

342
00:17:17,982 --> 00:17:18,983
What do I do?

343
00:17:19,782 --> 00:17:21,068
Get an apartment,

344
00:17:21,582 --> 00:17:24,028
get a job, pay child support.

345
00:17:24,102 --> 00:17:27,311
And then we will talk about visitation,
I promise.

346
00:17:27,862 --> 00:17:29,829
You're her hero, Scott.

347
00:17:30,781 --> 00:17:34,991
Just be the person
that she already thinks you are.

348
00:17:38,861 --> 00:17:40,306
(ENGINE STARTS)

349
00:17:47,741 --> 00:17:49,152
(HONKING MUSICAL CAR HORN)

350
00:17:49,741 --> 00:17:51,027
(GIGGLES)

351
00:17:57,541 --> 00:17:58,622
(FLUSHING)

352
00:17:58,701 --> 00:18:01,591
I'm sorry you have such deep concerns
about the Yellowjacket, Frank.

353
00:18:02,221 --> 00:18:04,189
Yeah. Well, uh...

354
00:18:04,261 --> 00:18:08,744
Unfortunately, we can't just do
whatever we want.

355
00:18:09,421 --> 00:18:11,025
It'd be nice though, right?

356
00:18:11,101 --> 00:18:12,262
(CHUCKLES)

357
00:18:12,461 --> 00:18:13,508
But there are laws.

358
00:18:14,101 --> 00:18:15,626
What laws? Of man?

359
00:18:15,701 --> 00:18:18,147
The laws of nature
transcend the laws of man.

360
00:18:18,221 --> 00:18:20,383
And I've transcended the laws of nature.

361
00:18:23,661 --> 00:18:26,744
Darren, I don't think you understand...

362
00:18:29,581 --> 00:18:30,742
Hmm.

363
00:18:32,821 --> 00:18:35,301
We still haven't worked out all the bugs.

364
00:18:40,541 --> 00:18:41,872
Goodbye, Frank.

365
00:18:55,421 --> 00:18:57,025
Thank you.

366
00:19:01,141 --> 00:19:03,906
You know, I've been thinking a lot
about gratitude lately.

367
00:19:03,981 --> 00:19:06,348
And today,
during my morning meditation,

368
00:19:06,421 --> 00:19:09,345
an interesting thought occurred to me,
and I think it might apply to you, too.

369
00:19:09,421 --> 00:19:10,707
How's that?

370
00:19:10,781 --> 00:19:12,590
Gratitude can be forgiveness.

371
00:19:13,981 --> 00:19:17,588
I've spent years carrying around
my anger for Hank Pym.

372
00:19:17,661 --> 00:19:20,267
I devoted my genius to him.

373
00:19:20,341 --> 00:19:22,184
I could have worked anywhere.

374
00:19:22,861 --> 00:19:24,511
I chose my mentor poorly.

375
00:19:25,341 --> 00:19:27,150
You didn't even have a choice.

376
00:19:27,861 --> 00:19:30,148
He never believed in you.

377
00:19:31,061 --> 00:19:35,783
It's a shame what we had to do,
but he forced us to do it, didn't he?

378
00:19:36,181 --> 00:19:39,185
But we shouldn't be angry,
we should be grateful.

379
00:19:39,941 --> 00:19:42,831
Because his failures as a mentor,

380
00:19:42,901 --> 00:19:45,029
as a father,

381
00:19:45,621 --> 00:19:48,704
forced us to spread our wings.

382
00:19:51,381 --> 00:19:53,463
You're a success, Darren.

383
00:19:54,301 --> 00:19:56,622
You deserve everything
coming your way.

384
00:20:16,741 --> 00:20:17,822
Ooh.

385
00:20:17,941 --> 00:20:19,591
Stop cheating.

386
00:20:20,421 --> 00:20:21,911
LUIS: Hey, what's up, hotshot?

387
00:20:23,301 --> 00:20:25,144
DAVE: Maybe he didn't hear you.

388
00:20:25,261 --> 00:20:26,262
How was the party?

389
00:20:33,101 --> 00:20:35,581
- Tell me about that tip.
- What?

390
00:20:35,661 --> 00:20:37,629
I wanna know about that tip.

391
00:20:37,701 --> 00:20:40,352
Oh, baby, it's on! It's so on, right now.

392
00:20:40,421 --> 00:20:42,822
Calm down, all right?
I just need to know where it came from.

393
00:20:42,901 --> 00:20:44,187
It's gotta be airtight.

394
00:20:44,901 --> 00:20:46,062
Okay.

395
00:20:46,141 --> 00:20:48,382
I was at a wine tasting
with my cousin Ernesto.

396
00:20:48,461 --> 00:20:50,782
Which was mainly reds,
and you know I don't like reds, man.

397
00:20:50,861 --> 00:20:53,181
But there was a rosé that saved the day.
It was delightful.

398
00:20:53,261 --> 00:20:55,867
<i>And then he tells me about this girl,
Emily, that we used to kick it with.</i>

399
00:20:55,941 --> 00:20:58,148
<i>It was actually the first pair of boobs
I ever touched.</i>

400
00:20:58,221 --> 00:20:59,871
It's the wrong details.

401
00:20:59,941 --> 00:21:01,272
It has nothing to do with the story.

402
00:21:01,381 --> 00:21:02,382
Go.

403
00:21:03,221 --> 00:21:06,862
LUIS: <i>So, uh, he tells me that she's
working as a housekeeper now, right?</i>

404
00:21:06,941 --> 00:21:10,263
<i>And she's dating this dude, Carlos,
who's a shot caller from across the bay.</i>

405
00:21:10,341 --> 00:21:13,424
<i>And she tells him about the dude
that she's cleaning for.</i>

406
00:21:13,501 --> 00:21:15,868
<i>Right? That he's like this big-shot CEO</i>

407
00:21:15,941 --> 00:21:18,023
<i>That is all retired now, but he's loaded.</i>

408
00:21:18,101 --> 00:21:21,822
<i>And so, Carlos and Ernesto
are on the same softball team,</i>

409
00:21:21,941 --> 00:21:23,545
<i>and they get to talking, right?</i>

410
00:21:23,621 --> 00:21:27,068
<i>And here comes the good part.
Carlos says, "Yo, man.</i>

411
00:21:27,141 --> 00:21:31,226
<i>"This guy's got a big-ass safe just
sitting in the basement, just chilling."</i>

412
00:21:31,301 --> 00:21:33,781
Of course Ernesto comes to me because
he knows I got mad thieving skills.

413
00:21:33,861 --> 00:21:34,862
<i>Of course, I ask him...</i>

414
00:21:34,941 --> 00:21:38,263
<i>"Did Emily tell Carlos to tell you
to get to me what kind of safe it was?"</i>

415
00:21:38,341 --> 00:21:39,581
<i>And he says, "Nah, dawg.</i>

416
00:21:39,661 --> 00:21:41,868
<i>"All she said is that it's super-legit</i>

417
00:21:41,941 --> 00:21:44,103
<i>"and whatever's in it, it's gotta be good."</i>

418
00:21:47,141 --> 00:21:48,141
What?

419
00:21:48,181 --> 00:21:50,661
Old man have safe.

420
00:21:50,781 --> 00:21:52,863
- (SNAPS FINGERS)
- And he's gone for a week.

421
00:21:52,941 --> 00:21:54,909
All right.
There's an old man, he's got a safe,

422
00:21:54,981 --> 00:21:56,107
and he's gone for a week.

423
00:21:56,181 --> 00:21:57,262
Let's just work with that.

424
00:21:57,341 --> 00:21:58,786
You know what I'm saying?

425
00:22:33,221 --> 00:22:35,030
(SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

426
00:22:47,901 --> 00:22:50,791
Landline's cut, cell signal's jammed.

427
00:22:50,861 --> 00:22:53,148
No one will be making
for distress call tonight.

428
00:22:53,221 --> 00:22:54,222
Comm check.

429
00:22:54,301 --> 00:22:55,461
- SCOTT: Check.
- DAVE: Check.

430
00:22:55,501 --> 00:22:57,708
Hey, if the job goes bad,
you know I got your back, right?

431
00:22:57,781 --> 00:22:59,021
Don't worry.

432
00:22:59,101 --> 00:23:01,308
It's not gonna happen.

433
00:23:03,781 --> 00:23:05,545
(CHUCKLES)
I love it when he gets cocky.

434
00:23:11,581 --> 00:23:12,662
Damn!

435
00:23:36,901 --> 00:23:37,902
(BEEPS)

436
00:23:40,461 --> 00:23:41,462
Alarm is dead.

437
00:23:41,581 --> 00:23:42,628
Nice.

438
00:23:44,941 --> 00:23:47,262
SCOTT: <i>All right,
I'm moving through the house.</i>

439
00:24:12,461 --> 00:24:14,350
There's a fingerprint lock on the door.

440
00:24:14,421 --> 00:24:17,027
It's got what?
Ernesto didn't tell me nothing about that.

441
00:24:17,101 --> 00:24:19,183
<i>Aw, man, are we screwed?</i>

442
00:24:19,261 --> 00:24:21,184
Not necessarily.

443
00:25:05,860 --> 00:25:07,703
(CLICKING AND BEEPING)

444
00:25:07,860 --> 00:25:09,100
(DOOR UNLOCKS)

445
00:25:09,180 --> 00:25:10,261
I'm in.

446
00:25:10,340 --> 00:25:13,549
No alarms have been triggered.
He's in like the Flynn.

447
00:25:17,380 --> 00:25:19,144
SCOTT: (SIGHS) Oh, man.

448
00:25:19,260 --> 00:25:20,591
LUIS: <i>What is it?</i>

449
00:25:21,220 --> 00:25:23,951
Well, they weren't kidding.
This safe is serious.

450
00:25:24,020 --> 00:25:26,261
LUIS: <i>How serious
are we talking, Scotty?</i>

451
00:25:26,340 --> 00:25:28,024
It's a Carbondale.

452
00:25:28,100 --> 00:25:29,511
It's from 1910.

453
00:25:29,580 --> 00:25:32,345
Made from the same steel as the Titanic.

454
00:25:32,420 --> 00:25:33,660
Wow.

455
00:25:33,740 --> 00:25:35,151
Can you crack it?

456
00:25:35,220 --> 00:25:38,622
SCOTT: Well, here's the thing.
It doesn't do so well in the cold.

457
00:25:38,740 --> 00:25:40,026
Remember what that iceberg did?

458
00:25:40,100 --> 00:25:41,829
Yeah, man. It killed DiCaprio.

459
00:25:41,900 --> 00:25:42,901
Killed everybody.

460
00:25:42,980 --> 00:25:44,505
Did not kill the Old lady.

461
00:25:44,620 --> 00:25:46,782
She still throw the jewel into the oceans.

462
00:25:59,540 --> 00:26:00,871
(WHIRRING)

463
00:26:14,220 --> 00:26:15,585
(GAS HISSING)

464
00:26:39,060 --> 00:26:40,550
LUIS: <i>What are you doing?</i>

465
00:26:40,620 --> 00:26:43,260
I poured water in the locking mechanism
and froze it with nitrogen.

466
00:26:43,820 --> 00:26:46,141
Ice expands. Metal doesn't.

467
00:26:46,620 --> 00:26:48,622
- LUIS: <i>What are you doing now?</i>
- Waiting.

468
00:26:48,780 --> 00:26:50,145
(METAL STRAINING)

469
00:26:50,220 --> 00:26:51,221
Waiting.

470
00:26:59,460 --> 00:27:00,461
Nice.

471
00:27:04,700 --> 00:27:06,350
LUIS: <i>What is it? Cash? Jewels?</i>

472
00:27:07,620 --> 00:27:09,463
- There's nothing here.
- What did you say?

473
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:12,989
- It's a suit.
- What?

474
00:27:13,620 --> 00:27:15,509
It's an old motorcycle suit.

475
00:27:16,540 --> 00:27:18,429
There's no cash, no jewelry, nothing?

476
00:27:18,500 --> 00:27:19,945
No.

477
00:27:20,820 --> 00:27:21,820
It's a bust.

478
00:27:21,860 --> 00:27:24,386
I'm really sorry, Scotty.

479
00:27:24,460 --> 00:27:26,224
I know you needed to score.

480
00:27:31,500 --> 00:27:33,025
(FAINT BEEPING)

481
00:27:51,020 --> 00:27:52,306
(BLEATING)

482
00:28:01,020 --> 00:28:02,351
I thought we were using mice.

483
00:28:03,180 --> 00:28:04,341
What's the difference?

484
00:28:05,700 --> 00:28:10,581
Commence Experiment 34-C.
Organic atomic reduction.

485
00:28:10,660 --> 00:28:12,469
- (BLEATING CONTINUES)
- Darren, maybe we should think...

486
00:28:12,540 --> 00:28:15,020
Shrinking organic tissue
is the centerpiece of this technology.

487
00:28:15,100 --> 00:28:17,102
I can't go to the buyers
with half a breakthrough.

488
00:28:21,540 --> 00:28:22,905
(WHIRRING)

489
00:28:32,460 --> 00:28:33,461
(GASPS)

490
00:28:41,620 --> 00:28:45,864
Experiment 34-C results,

491
00:28:45,940 --> 00:28:46,987
negative.

492
00:28:51,380 --> 00:28:54,941
Sanitize the work station.
Bring in subject 35-C.

493
00:29:01,860 --> 00:29:03,100
(SCOFFS)

494
00:29:06,180 --> 00:29:07,750
SCOTT: Why would you lock this up?

495
00:29:29,460 --> 00:29:31,701
This is so weird.

496
00:29:37,460 --> 00:29:38,985
(DEVICE BEEPING)

497
00:30:03,660 --> 00:30:05,071
LUIS: Scotty, what's up, man?

498
00:30:10,340 --> 00:30:12,707
SCOTT: I wonder... What is this?

499
00:30:17,860 --> 00:30:19,350
(SCREAMING)

500
00:30:20,340 --> 00:30:22,149
(METAL CLANGS LOUDLY)

501
00:30:32,500 --> 00:30:34,150
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

502
00:30:43,060 --> 00:30:46,621
HANK: <i>The world sure seems different
from down here, doesn't it, Scott?</i>

503
00:30:46,700 --> 00:30:49,101
SCOTT: What? Who said that?

504
00:30:49,180 --> 00:30:50,784
(LOUD FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

505
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:56,429
SCOTT: (FAINTLY) Luis, down here!

506
00:30:57,140 --> 00:31:00,861
HANK: <i>It's a trial by fire, Scott.
Or, in this case,</i>

507
00:31:00,940 --> 00:31:01,987
<i>water.</i>

508
00:31:10,220 --> 00:31:11,381
(SCREAMING)

509
00:31:14,660 --> 00:31:15,786
(GASPS)

510
00:31:18,060 --> 00:31:20,347
(SCREAMING)

511
00:31:23,020 --> 00:31:24,101
(GROANS)

512
00:31:26,460 --> 00:31:28,746
HANK: <i>Guess you're tougher
than you thought.</i>

513
00:31:29,859 --> 00:31:31,304
(PANTS UNZIPPING)

514
00:31:31,379 --> 00:31:32,904
SCOTT: Oh, I don't want to see this!

515
00:31:33,579 --> 00:31:34,819
Luis!

516
00:31:35,819 --> 00:31:37,059
(SCREAMING)

517
00:31:39,739 --> 00:31:40,786
Son of a...

518
00:31:40,859 --> 00:31:42,429
(LOUD MUSIC PLAYING)

519
00:31:51,779 --> 00:31:53,224
(CROWD CHEERING)

520
00:32:05,619 --> 00:32:06,620
(GRUNTING)

521
00:32:30,339 --> 00:32:31,340
(YELLS)

522
00:32:33,859 --> 00:32:35,623
(PANTING)

523
00:32:37,459 --> 00:32:39,029
(GROWLING)

524
00:32:40,299 --> 00:32:41,744
(SNIFFING)

525
00:32:41,819 --> 00:32:42,820
(SHRIEKS)

526
00:32:42,899 --> 00:32:43,900
(SCOTT GASPS)

527
00:32:49,099 --> 00:32:50,544
(SCREAMING)

528
00:32:52,259 --> 00:32:53,829
(CAR ROOF CLANGS)

529
00:32:56,419 --> 00:32:57,750
(THUDDING)

530
00:32:57,899 --> 00:32:59,310
What the hell?

531
00:33:00,379 --> 00:33:02,859
HANK: <i>Not bad for a test drive.</i>

532
00:33:02,939 --> 00:33:05,067
<i>Keep the suit. I'll be in touch.</i>

533
00:33:05,139 --> 00:33:07,187
No! No! No, thank you!

534
00:33:19,339 --> 00:33:21,467
- (SIRENS BLARE)
- POLICEMAN: Get down on the ground!

535
00:33:21,539 --> 00:33:22,950
You are under arrest!

536
00:33:23,019 --> 00:33:25,784
No, I didn't steal anything!
I was returning something I stole.

537
00:33:25,899 --> 00:33:26,900
Oh...

538
00:33:29,219 --> 00:33:30,869
POLICEMAN: Don't move.

539
00:33:34,859 --> 00:33:36,145
PAXTON: <i>You know,
you almost had us convinced</i>

540
00:33:36,219 --> 00:33:38,347
that you were gonna change your ways.

541
00:33:38,899 --> 00:33:41,061
They were really rooting for you.

542
00:33:42,699 --> 00:33:44,701
It's gonna break their hearts.

543
00:33:47,459 --> 00:33:49,860
- You got a visitor.
- Who?

544
00:33:50,299 --> 00:33:51,300
Your lawyer.

545
00:33:52,099 --> 00:33:53,430
My lawyer?

546
00:33:56,539 --> 00:33:58,985
HANK: I told you I'd be in touch, Scott.

547
00:33:59,779 --> 00:34:03,465
I'm starting to think that
you prefer the inside of a jail cell.

548
00:34:04,299 --> 00:34:05,300
Oh, man.

549
00:34:05,859 --> 00:34:06,985
HANK: Sit down.

550
00:34:10,659 --> 00:34:13,663
Sir, I'm sorry I stole the suit.

551
00:34:13,739 --> 00:34:15,628
I don't even wanna know
why you have it.

552
00:34:15,699 --> 00:34:17,667
Maggie was right about you.

553
00:34:19,259 --> 00:34:20,260
How do you know about...

554
00:34:20,339 --> 00:34:22,379
No wonder she's trying
to keep you away from Cassie.

555
00:34:23,619 --> 00:34:25,348
The moment things get hard,

556
00:34:25,419 --> 00:34:26,864
you turn right back to crime.

557
00:34:29,379 --> 00:34:31,541
The way I see it,
you have a choice.

558
00:34:31,619 --> 00:34:34,270
You can either spend
the rest of your life in prison,

559
00:34:35,099 --> 00:34:36,942
or go back to your cell

560
00:34:37,539 --> 00:34:40,019
and await further instructions.

561
00:34:40,099 --> 00:34:41,510
I don't understand.

562
00:34:41,579 --> 00:34:43,741
No, I don't expect you to.

563
00:34:43,819 --> 00:34:46,868
But you don't have many options
right now, and quite frankly,

564
00:34:46,939 --> 00:34:48,270
neither do I.

565
00:34:49,179 --> 00:34:53,025
Why do you think I let you
steal that suit in the first place?

566
00:34:53,099 --> 00:34:54,260
What?

567
00:34:59,779 --> 00:35:01,065
(INAUDIBLE)

568
00:35:04,499 --> 00:35:07,742
Second chances don't come around
all that much.

569
00:35:07,819 --> 00:35:10,868
So, next time you think
you might see one,

570
00:35:10,939 --> 00:35:15,422
I suggest you take a real close look at it.

571
00:35:27,459 --> 00:35:29,666
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>You're my bestest friend!</i>

572
00:35:29,739 --> 00:35:31,779
MAGGIE: Are you sure you
don't want a different toy?

573
00:35:31,819 --> 00:35:33,742
No, I love this one.

574
00:35:34,339 --> 00:35:37,070
Okay. Well, get some sleep. I love you.

575
00:35:37,699 --> 00:35:39,110
- Mommy?
- Hmm?

576
00:35:39,179 --> 00:35:41,500
Is Daddy a bad man?

577
00:35:42,099 --> 00:35:44,943
I heard some grownups say he's bad.

578
00:35:45,739 --> 00:35:47,025
No.

579
00:35:47,899 --> 00:35:50,948
Daddy just gets confused sometimes,
you know?

580
00:35:56,299 --> 00:35:57,710
(FLY BUZZING)

581
00:36:14,579 --> 00:36:15,785
(SUIT ZAPS)

582
00:36:18,379 --> 00:36:20,029
(DOOR BUZZING OPEN)

583
00:36:42,379 --> 00:36:45,383
HANK: <i>Smart choice.
You actually listened, for once.</i>

584
00:36:46,419 --> 00:36:47,420
<i>Under the door.</i>

585
00:36:47,499 --> 00:36:48,500
(PANTING)

586
00:36:48,579 --> 00:36:49,705
(ALARM RINGING)

587
00:36:52,899 --> 00:36:54,139
Okay, where to now?

588
00:36:54,219 --> 00:36:56,221
- HANK: <i>Hang tight.</i>
- Oh, God.

589
00:36:59,059 --> 00:37:00,060
What, what?

590
00:37:00,139 --> 00:37:01,140
Where the hell did he go?

591
00:37:01,219 --> 00:37:02,505
I have no idea.
He just vanished.

592
00:37:02,579 --> 00:37:04,547
Set up a five-block perimeter. Now!

593
00:37:04,619 --> 00:37:05,825
SCOTT: Get back! Get back!

594
00:37:05,899 --> 00:37:08,505
HANK: <i>Scott, these are my associates.</i>

595
00:37:08,939 --> 00:37:10,429
SCOTT: Is that a camera on an ant?

596
00:37:10,499 --> 00:37:12,388
Yeah, sure. Why not?

597
00:37:12,459 --> 00:37:13,460
Where's the car?

598
00:37:13,539 --> 00:37:15,189
HANK: <i>No car. We've got wings.</i>

599
00:37:15,259 --> 00:37:16,545
<i>Incoming!</i>

600
00:37:26,459 --> 00:37:29,508
<i>Put your foot on the central node
and mount the thorax.</i>

601
00:37:29,579 --> 00:37:31,579
- How safe is...
<i>- Just get on the damn ant, Scott!</i>

602
00:37:39,819 --> 00:37:41,059
(SIRENS BLARING)

603
00:37:44,659 --> 00:37:48,186
SCOTT: Why am I on a police car?
Shouldn't I not be on a police car?

604
00:37:48,299 --> 00:37:50,700
HANK: <i>So they can give you a lift
past their five-block perimeter.</i>

605
00:37:50,779 --> 00:37:52,429
SCOTT: All right.

606
00:37:52,499 --> 00:37:54,467
- Now, what's the next move?
<i>- Hang on tight.</i>

607
00:37:54,539 --> 00:37:56,303
SCOTT: Oh, this is easy!
I'm getting the hang of this.

608
00:37:56,379 --> 00:37:58,029
Yank up to go up.
It's like a horse.

609
00:37:58,099 --> 00:38:00,147
HANK: <i>You're throwing 247 off balance.</i>

610
00:38:00,219 --> 00:38:01,630
Wait, his name is 247?

611
00:38:01,699 --> 00:38:03,463
<i>He doesn't have a name,
he has a number, Scott.</i>

612
00:38:03,539 --> 00:38:06,065
<i>Do you have any idea
how many ants there are?</i>

613
00:38:06,179 --> 00:38:07,908
- (CAR HONKING)
- SCOTT: Whoa!

614
00:38:07,979 --> 00:38:09,822
HANK: <i>Maybe it's... Maybe it's 248.</i>

615
00:38:09,939 --> 00:38:11,384
SCOTT: No, no! Vertigo, vertigo!

616
00:38:11,459 --> 00:38:13,461
- HANK: <i>No, I think it's 247.</i>
- Wait.

617
00:38:13,819 --> 00:38:15,389
HANK: <i>Hang on tight!</i>

618
00:38:15,459 --> 00:38:17,427
SCOTT: I think
I'm getting the hang of this.

619
00:38:17,539 --> 00:38:20,383
HANK: <i>I am controlling 247.
He is not listening to you.</i>

620
00:38:20,499 --> 00:38:21,499
SCOTT: What?

621
00:38:21,539 --> 00:38:23,428
- Can I make one little request?
<i>- No.</i>

622
00:38:23,499 --> 00:38:24,910
(BUZZING)

623
00:38:24,979 --> 00:38:26,822
SCOTT: Stop, 247! Time out, time out.

624
00:38:27,618 --> 00:38:28,779
Time out.

625
00:38:28,858 --> 00:38:29,939
All right, hold on.

626
00:38:30,018 --> 00:38:31,907
Just wait! Whoa!

627
00:38:32,498 --> 00:38:34,148
What happens
if I throw up in this helmet?

628
00:38:34,218 --> 00:38:37,586
HANK: <i>It's my helmet, Scott.
You do not throw up.</i>

629
00:38:37,658 --> 00:38:39,262
SCOTT: Let's set her down, all right?

630
00:38:39,338 --> 00:38:40,339
I'm getting light-headed.

631
00:38:40,418 --> 00:38:41,499
<i>Hang on, Scott.</i>

632
00:38:42,178 --> 00:38:44,146
I'm getting a little light...

633
00:38:44,218 --> 00:38:46,141
I need a snooze button.

634
00:38:46,658 --> 00:38:49,025
Hit me in 5 minutes.

635
00:38:59,018 --> 00:39:00,827
(FAINT TAPPING)

636
00:39:04,018 --> 00:39:05,019
(GASPS)

637
00:39:07,618 --> 00:39:08,858
Hello.

638
00:39:12,298 --> 00:39:13,459
Who are you?

639
00:39:15,538 --> 00:39:18,303
Have you been standing there,
watching me sleep, this whole time?

640
00:39:18,378 --> 00:39:19,459
Yes.

641
00:39:19,538 --> 00:39:20,699
Why?

642
00:39:21,458 --> 00:39:23,698
Because the last time you were here,
you stole something.

643
00:39:24,778 --> 00:39:26,701
Oh. Oh.

644
00:39:27,378 --> 00:39:28,539
Hey, look...

645
00:39:29,458 --> 00:39:30,459
Whoa!

646
00:39:35,098 --> 00:39:36,827
HOPE: <i>Paraponera clavata.</i>

647
00:39:36,898 --> 00:39:38,388
Giant tropical bullet ants,

648
00:39:38,458 --> 00:39:40,058
ranked highest
on the Schmidt pain index.

649
00:39:40,098 --> 00:39:41,978
They're here to keep an eye on you
when I can't.

650
00:39:43,098 --> 00:39:45,863
Dr. Pym's waiting for you downstairs.

651
00:39:46,458 --> 00:39:47,459
Who?

652
00:39:48,498 --> 00:39:49,704
(GROANS)

653
00:39:49,818 --> 00:39:50,819
Hey!

654
00:39:50,898 --> 00:39:53,583
Um... Whose pajamas are these?

655
00:39:59,978 --> 00:40:01,901
How am I supposed to do this?

656
00:40:08,138 --> 00:40:11,221
All right, just one step at a time.

657
00:40:13,338 --> 00:40:14,339
Ugh!

658
00:40:16,018 --> 00:40:20,501
You don't bite me,
I don't step on you. Deal?

659
00:40:24,298 --> 00:40:26,619
HOPE: I could take down the servers
and Cross wouldn't even know it.

660
00:40:26,698 --> 00:40:27,904
We don't need this guy.

661
00:40:27,978 --> 00:40:30,458
I assume that you've already
met my daughter, Hope.

662
00:40:30,538 --> 00:40:33,109
I did. She's great.

663
00:40:33,178 --> 00:40:35,419
She doesn't think that we need you.

664
00:40:35,498 --> 00:40:36,898
We don't. We can do this ourselves.

665
00:40:36,938 --> 00:40:40,181
I go to all this effort
to let you steal my suit,

666
00:40:40,258 --> 00:40:42,829
and then Hope has you arrested.

667
00:40:42,898 --> 00:40:45,902
Okay, we can try this and when he fails,
I'll do it myself.

668
00:40:46,018 --> 00:40:47,622
She's a little bit anxious.

669
00:40:48,178 --> 00:40:49,623
It has to do with this job,

670
00:40:49,698 --> 00:40:52,224
which, judging by the fact
that you're sitting opposite me,

671
00:40:52,298 --> 00:40:54,539
I take it that you're interested in.

672
00:40:54,618 --> 00:40:55,744
What job?

673
00:40:55,818 --> 00:40:56,979
Would you like some tea?

674
00:40:57,498 --> 00:40:59,227
Uh... Sure.

675
00:40:59,298 --> 00:41:00,902
I was very impressed with

676
00:41:00,978 --> 00:41:03,788
how you managed to get
past my security system.

677
00:41:05,018 --> 00:41:08,022
Freezing that metal
was particularly clever.

678
00:41:08,098 --> 00:41:09,543
Were you watching me?

679
00:41:09,618 --> 00:41:12,827
Scott, I've been watching you for a while.

680
00:41:12,898 --> 00:41:15,299
Ever since you robbed Vista Corp.

681
00:41:16,778 --> 00:41:18,542
Oh! Excuse me.

682
00:41:18,618 --> 00:41:20,586
"Burgled" Vista Corp.

683
00:41:22,218 --> 00:41:26,189
Vista's security system was one of
the most advanced in the business.

684
00:41:26,258 --> 00:41:27,987
It was supposed to be unbeatable.

685
00:41:28,058 --> 00:41:29,981
But you beat it.

686
00:41:30,058 --> 00:41:31,389
Would you like some sugar?

687
00:41:31,458 --> 00:41:33,028
Yeah, thanks.

688
00:41:36,938 --> 00:41:38,178
You know what?
I'm okay.

689
00:41:43,138 --> 00:41:45,300
How do you make them do that?

690
00:41:45,378 --> 00:41:48,029
Ants can lift objects
50 times their weight.

691
00:41:48,098 --> 00:41:51,739
They build, farm,
they cooperate with each other.

692
00:41:51,818 --> 00:41:53,980
Right. But how do you
make them do that?

693
00:41:55,938 --> 00:42:01,547
I use electromagnetic waves
to stimulate their olfactory nerve center.

694
00:42:02,738 --> 00:42:04,627
I speak to them.

695
00:42:04,698 --> 00:42:07,099
I can go anywhere, hear anything,

696
00:42:07,178 --> 00:42:08,589
and see everything.

697
00:42:08,658 --> 00:42:10,547
And still know absolutely nothing.

698
00:42:11,138 --> 00:42:12,185
I'm late to meet Cross.

699
00:42:13,658 --> 00:42:15,228
(BREATHING HARD)

700
00:42:16,018 --> 00:42:17,782
Uh... Dr. Pym?

701
00:42:17,858 --> 00:42:20,179
You don't need to raise your hand, Scott.

702
00:42:20,738 --> 00:42:23,389
Sorry, I just have one question.

703
00:42:23,458 --> 00:42:25,586
Who are you, who is she,
what the hell's going on,

704
00:42:25,658 --> 00:42:27,308
and can I go back to jail now?

705
00:42:27,378 --> 00:42:28,789
Come with me.

706
00:42:29,418 --> 00:42:33,548
40 years ago, I created a formula
that altered atomic relative distance.

707
00:42:33,618 --> 00:42:34,824
SCOTT: Huh?

708
00:42:34,898 --> 00:42:37,139
I learned how to change
the distance between atoms.

709
00:42:37,218 --> 00:42:38,947
That's what powers the suit.

710
00:42:39,018 --> 00:42:40,702
That's why it works.

711
00:42:41,898 --> 00:42:42,899
SCOTT: Wow.

712
00:42:45,418 --> 00:42:47,341
(MACHINERY POWERING UP)

713
00:42:48,298 --> 00:42:49,902
- Whoa!
- But it was dangerous.

714
00:42:50,578 --> 00:42:52,660
It was too dangerous.

715
00:42:53,898 --> 00:42:55,866
So I hid it from the world.

716
00:42:56,698 --> 00:42:59,668
And that's when I switched gears
and I started my own company.

717
00:43:00,578 --> 00:43:01,659
Pym Tech.

718
00:43:01,778 --> 00:43:02,904
Yes.

719
00:43:03,858 --> 00:43:07,658
I took on a young protégé
called Darren Cross.

720
00:43:07,738 --> 00:43:08,978
SCOTT: Darren Cross.

721
00:43:09,058 --> 00:43:10,105
He's a big deal.

722
00:43:10,178 --> 00:43:12,658
But before he was a big deal,
he was my assistant.

723
00:43:12,738 --> 00:43:17,062
I thought I saw something in him.
The son I never had, perhaps.

724
00:43:17,138 --> 00:43:19,459
He was brilliant,
but as we became close,

725
00:43:19,538 --> 00:43:23,099
he began to suspect
that I wasn't telling him everything.

726
00:43:23,218 --> 00:43:26,859
He heard rumors about
what was called the Pym Particle,

727
00:43:26,938 --> 00:43:30,147
and he became obsessed
with recreating my formula.

728
00:43:30,658 --> 00:43:31,705
But I wouldn't help him.

729
00:43:31,778 --> 00:43:35,624
So he conspired against me and
he voted me out of my own company.

730
00:43:35,698 --> 00:43:37,223
How could he do that?

731
00:43:37,298 --> 00:43:40,108
The board's chairman
is my daughter, Hope.

732
00:43:40,178 --> 00:43:41,509
She was the deciding vote.

733
00:43:43,658 --> 00:43:45,103
But she came back to me

734
00:43:45,178 --> 00:43:48,546
when she saw how close
Cross was to cracking my formula.

735
00:43:49,618 --> 00:43:51,859
The process is highly volatile.

736
00:43:51,938 --> 00:43:54,782
If one isn't protected
by a specialized helmet,

737
00:43:54,858 --> 00:43:57,748
it can affect the brain's chemistry.

738
00:43:58,378 --> 00:44:00,779
I don't think Darren realizes this,

739
00:44:00,858 --> 00:44:03,702
and, you know, he's not
the most stable guy to begin with.

740
00:44:04,378 --> 00:44:06,540
So, what do you want from me?

741
00:44:08,618 --> 00:44:12,304
Scott, I believe that everyone deserves
a shot at redemption.

742
00:44:12,378 --> 00:44:13,379
Do you?

743
00:44:13,458 --> 00:44:14,903
I do.

744
00:44:15,578 --> 00:44:17,068
If you can help me,

745
00:44:17,138 --> 00:44:20,859
I promise I can help you be
with your daughter again.

746
00:44:21,898 --> 00:44:24,265
Now, are you ready to redeem yourself?

747
00:44:24,858 --> 00:44:25,939
Absolutely.

748
00:44:26,018 --> 00:44:29,784
My days of breaking into places
and stealing shit are done.

749
00:44:30,858 --> 00:44:32,223
What do you want me to do?

750
00:44:32,298 --> 00:44:35,700
I want you to break into a place
and steal some shit.

751
00:44:37,338 --> 00:44:38,499
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

752
00:44:38,578 --> 00:44:40,178
Are you gonna be home
for dinner tonight?

753
00:44:42,178 --> 00:44:44,419
Uh, yeah. I'll pick something up.
Text me.

754
00:44:44,498 --> 00:44:45,784
Okay. Good news?

755
00:44:46,138 --> 00:44:48,300
Uh... I don't know. It's news.

756
00:44:48,378 --> 00:44:50,904
Are you trying to find my daddy?

757
00:44:52,738 --> 00:44:54,547
Yeah, I am, sweetheart.

758
00:44:55,818 --> 00:44:57,263
I just want your daddy to be safe.

759
00:44:57,338 --> 00:44:59,466
Hope you don't catch him.

760
00:45:15,058 --> 00:45:16,389
(BLEATING)

761
00:45:30,937 --> 00:45:32,541
(BLEATING CONTINUES)

762
00:45:45,617 --> 00:45:47,267
This isn't the first time these guys

763
00:45:47,337 --> 00:45:50,147
have tried to get their hands
on game-changing weaponry.

764
00:45:50,217 --> 00:45:54,267
That's Mitchell Carson,
Ex-Head of Defense at S.H.I.E.L.D.

765
00:45:54,337 --> 00:45:56,704
Presently in the business
of toppling governments.

766
00:45:57,257 --> 00:45:59,146
He always wanted my tech.

767
00:45:59,217 --> 00:46:02,539
And now, unless we break in
and steal the Yellowjacket

768
00:46:02,617 --> 00:46:04,745
and destroy all the data,

769
00:46:05,417 --> 00:46:10,787
Darren Cross is gonna unleash chaos
upon the world.

770
00:46:13,177 --> 00:46:17,262
I think our first move should be
calling the Avengers.

771
00:46:17,337 --> 00:46:18,463
(HANK SCOFFS)

772
00:46:18,577 --> 00:46:20,341
I spent half my life

773
00:46:20,417 --> 00:46:23,580
trying to keep this technology
out of the hands of a Stark.

774
00:46:23,657 --> 00:46:27,423
I'm sure as hell not gonna
hand-deliver it to one now.

775
00:46:27,497 --> 00:46:30,899
This is not some cute technology
like the Iron Man suit.

776
00:46:30,977 --> 00:46:33,503
This could change the texture of reality.

777
00:46:35,457 --> 00:46:39,507
Besides, they're probably too busy
dropping cities out of the sky.

778
00:46:40,137 --> 00:46:42,060
Okay, then why don't you
just send the ants?

779
00:46:42,737 --> 00:46:44,865
Scott, they are ants.

780
00:46:44,937 --> 00:46:48,862
Ants, they can do a lot of things,
but they still need a leader.

781
00:46:49,937 --> 00:46:54,784
Somebody that could infiltrate a place
that's designed to prevent infiltration.

782
00:46:54,857 --> 00:46:58,464
Hank, I'm a thief, all right? I mean,
I'm a good thief, but this is insane.

783
00:46:58,537 --> 00:47:00,619
He's right, Hank.
And you know it.

784
00:47:00,697 --> 00:47:03,303
You've seen the footage,
you know what Cross is capable of.

785
00:47:03,857 --> 00:47:05,427
I was against using him
when we had months,

786
00:47:05,497 --> 00:47:07,465
and now we have days.

787
00:47:07,537 --> 00:47:08,538
I'm wearing the suit.

788
00:47:08,617 --> 00:47:10,028
Absolutely not!

789
00:47:10,097 --> 00:47:13,021
I know the facility inside and out.
I know how Cross thinks.

790
00:47:13,097 --> 00:47:14,667
I know this mission
better than anybody here.

791
00:47:14,737 --> 00:47:17,422
We need you close to Cross.
Otherwise, this mission cannot work.

792
00:47:17,497 --> 00:47:19,943
- We don't have time to screw around!
- Hope, please listen to me...

793
00:47:20,017 --> 00:47:21,587
He is a criminal!
I'm your daughter.

794
00:47:21,657 --> 00:47:22,988
- (SLAMS TABLE)
- No!

795
00:47:37,417 --> 00:47:38,657
(SIGHS)

796
00:47:53,617 --> 00:47:54,982
(SIGHING)

797
00:48:01,377 --> 00:48:03,141
She's right, Hank.

798
00:48:03,217 --> 00:48:04,901
I'm not your guy.

799
00:48:05,497 --> 00:48:07,818
- Why don't you wear the suit?
- (SIGHING)

800
00:48:07,897 --> 00:48:10,104
You think I don't want to?

801
00:48:10,177 --> 00:48:11,417
I can't.

802
00:48:13,057 --> 00:48:14,900
I spent years wearing it,

803
00:48:15,537 --> 00:48:17,744
and it took a toll on me.

804
00:48:23,737 --> 00:48:24,863
(SIGHS)

805
00:48:25,137 --> 00:48:26,468
You're our only option.

806
00:48:31,937 --> 00:48:34,781
Before Hope lost her mother,

807
00:48:34,857 --> 00:48:38,782
she used to look at me like
I was the greatest man in the world.

808
00:48:40,657 --> 00:48:43,945
And now she looks at me
and there's just disappointment.

809
00:48:47,257 --> 00:48:49,259
It's too late for me,

810
00:48:50,497 --> 00:48:52,226
but not for you.

811
00:48:52,337 --> 00:48:54,260
This is your chance.

812
00:48:54,337 --> 00:48:57,944
The chance to earn that look
in your daughter's eyes.

813
00:48:58,017 --> 00:49:01,908
To become the hero
that she already thinks you are.

814
00:49:02,617 --> 00:49:05,143
It's not about saving our world.

815
00:49:06,017 --> 00:49:08,827
It's about saving theirs.

816
00:49:11,777 --> 00:49:13,620
Damn. That was a good speech.

817
00:49:14,217 --> 00:49:15,298
Scott,

818
00:49:16,337 --> 00:49:20,137
I need you to be the Ant-Man.

819
00:49:23,297 --> 00:49:24,583
In the right hands,

820
00:49:24,657 --> 00:49:27,945
the relationship between man and suit
is symbiotic.

821
00:49:28,017 --> 00:49:31,783
The suit has power.
The man harnesses that power.

822
00:49:31,857 --> 00:49:34,701
You need to be skillful, agile,
and above all,

823
00:49:34,777 --> 00:49:35,983
you need to be fast.

824
00:49:36,057 --> 00:49:37,980
You should be able to shrink and grow

825
00:49:38,057 --> 00:49:39,263
on a dime.

826
00:49:39,857 --> 00:49:43,179
So your size always suits your needs.

827
00:49:44,217 --> 00:49:46,106
Now dive through the keyhole, Scott.

828
00:49:46,177 --> 00:49:50,148
You charge big, you dive small,
then you emerge big.

829
00:49:52,017 --> 00:49:53,542
- (THUDDING)
- SCOTT: Ow!

830
00:49:54,857 --> 00:49:55,858
- (THUDDING)
- Ahhh!

831
00:49:56,297 --> 00:49:57,867
- (THUDDING)
- Ow!

832
00:49:58,057 --> 00:49:59,183
Useless.

833
00:50:01,497 --> 00:50:02,942
When you're small,
energy's compressed,

834
00:50:03,017 --> 00:50:04,940
so you have the force
of a 200-pound man

835
00:50:05,017 --> 00:50:08,305
behind a fist a 100th of an inch wide.
You're like a bullet.

836
00:50:08,377 --> 00:50:11,745
You punch too hard, you kill someone.
Too soft, it's a love tap.

837
00:50:11,817 --> 00:50:13,262
In other words,
you have to know how to punch.

838
00:50:13,377 --> 00:50:15,141
I was in prison for three years.
I know how to punch.

839
00:50:15,217 --> 00:50:16,946
Show me.

840
00:50:17,017 --> 00:50:18,777
- Terrible.
- You wanna show me how to punch?

841
00:50:19,377 --> 00:50:20,378
Show me...

842
00:50:20,697 --> 00:50:21,744
(GROANS)

843
00:50:21,817 --> 00:50:23,581
That's how you punch.

844
00:50:23,657 --> 00:50:26,422
- She's been looking forward to this.
- No kidding.

845
00:50:26,497 --> 00:50:29,148
Hope trained in martial arts
at a difficult time.

846
00:50:29,217 --> 00:50:31,337
Oh, by "difficult time,"
he means when my mother died.

847
00:50:31,377 --> 00:50:33,425
We lost her in a plane crash.

848
00:50:33,497 --> 00:50:35,226
It's bad enough
you won't tell me how she died.

849
00:50:35,297 --> 00:50:36,867
Could you please stop
telling me that lie?

850
00:50:36,937 --> 00:50:38,701
We're working, here.

851
00:50:41,897 --> 00:50:43,617
All right, princess.
Let's get back to work.

852
00:50:44,377 --> 00:50:46,618
Were you going for the hand?

853
00:50:52,937 --> 00:50:55,065
You know, I think this regulator
is holding me back.

854
00:50:55,137 --> 00:50:57,822
Do not screw with the regulator.

855
00:50:57,897 --> 00:50:59,661
If that regulator is compromised,

856
00:50:59,737 --> 00:51:01,307
you would go subatomic.

857
00:51:01,377 --> 00:51:02,742
What does that mean?

858
00:51:03,817 --> 00:51:05,979
It means that you would enter
a quantum realm.

859
00:51:06,097 --> 00:51:07,508
What does that mean?

860
00:51:07,577 --> 00:51:12,105
It means that you would enter a reality
where all concepts of time and space

861
00:51:12,177 --> 00:51:13,224
become irrelevant

862
00:51:13,297 --> 00:51:16,141
as you shrink for all eternity.

863
00:51:16,897 --> 00:51:19,468
Everything that you know

864
00:51:19,537 --> 00:51:20,868
and love,

865
00:51:21,777 --> 00:51:23,347
gone forever.

866
00:51:24,257 --> 00:51:27,579
Cool. Yeah, if it ain't broke...

867
00:51:27,657 --> 00:51:28,988
You've learned about the suit,

868
00:51:29,057 --> 00:51:31,788
but you've yet to learn
about your greatest allies,

869
00:51:33,097 --> 00:51:34,144
the ants.

870
00:51:34,737 --> 00:51:36,023
Loyal, brave,

871
00:51:36,097 --> 00:51:37,906
<i>and your partners on this job.</i>

872
00:51:43,937 --> 00:51:46,861
HOPE: Paratrechina longicornis.
<i>Commonly known as crazy ants.</i>

873
00:51:46,937 --> 00:51:49,144
<i>They're lightning fast
and can conduct electricity,</i>

874
00:51:49,217 --> 00:51:51,663
<i>which makes them useful
to fry out enemy electronics.</i>

875
00:51:51,737 --> 00:51:53,421
You're not so crazy.

876
00:51:53,657 --> 00:51:55,819
- (SQUEAKS)
- Hey!

877
00:51:55,937 --> 00:51:57,223
(CHUCKLING) You're cute.

878
00:51:59,137 --> 00:52:00,423
(SCREAMING)

879
00:52:05,697 --> 00:52:07,825
That was a lot scarier a second ago.

880
00:52:08,217 --> 00:52:09,457
(BOTH GRUNTING)

881
00:52:14,377 --> 00:52:15,503
(GROANS)

882
00:52:15,977 --> 00:52:17,024
(GROANING)

883
00:52:17,177 --> 00:52:20,863
It looks like the Futures Lab
has its own isolated power supply.

884
00:52:20,937 --> 00:52:22,860
HOPE: <i>There's a security guard posted
around the clock.</i>

885
00:52:22,937 --> 00:52:25,543
We'll need you to take him out
to deactivate the security systems.

886
00:52:25,617 --> 00:52:28,187
SCOTT: Okay, who's next?

887
00:52:30,216 --> 00:52:31,547
HOPE: Paraponera clavata.

888
00:52:31,616 --> 00:52:33,266
SCOTT: <i>I know. Bullet ants, right?</i>

889
00:52:33,336 --> 00:52:34,906
Number 1 on the Schmidt pain index?

890
00:52:35,016 --> 00:52:36,825
Hey, guys.
Remember me from the bedroom?

891
00:52:37,656 --> 00:52:38,657
(YELLS)

892
00:52:39,616 --> 00:52:41,576
HOPE: <i>The Yellowjacket pod
is hermetically sealed,</i>

893
00:52:41,616 --> 00:52:42,947
And the only access point is a tube

894
00:52:43,016 --> 00:52:45,781
we estimate to be about
5 millimeters in diameter.

895
00:52:45,856 --> 00:52:47,699
Why do I have a sick feeling
in my stomach?

896
00:52:47,776 --> 00:52:49,983
HOPE: <i>The tube is protected
by a laser grid,</i>

897
00:52:50,056 --> 00:52:51,820
and we can only power that down
for 15 seconds.

898
00:52:51,896 --> 00:52:54,502
You're gonna need to signal
the crazy ants to blow the servers,

899
00:52:54,576 --> 00:52:58,661
retrieve the suit, and exit the vaults
before the backup power comes on.

900
00:52:58,736 --> 00:53:00,898
HOPE: Camponotus pennsylvanicus.

901
00:53:01,616 --> 00:53:03,176
Alternatively known as a carpenter ant.

902
00:53:03,216 --> 00:53:06,026
Ideal for ground and air transport.

903
00:53:06,096 --> 00:53:07,780
Wait a minute, I know this guy.

904
00:53:09,056 --> 00:53:11,377
I'm gonna call him "Ant-thony."

905
00:53:11,456 --> 00:53:12,696
That's good. That's very good.

906
00:53:12,776 --> 00:53:17,418
Because this time, you're really gonna
have to learn how to control him.

907
00:53:17,496 --> 00:53:20,227
<i>Tell them to put the sugar in the teacup.</i>

908
00:53:20,376 --> 00:53:21,582
(GRUNTING)

909
00:53:23,176 --> 00:53:24,462
Aw! You okay?
Did I hurt...

910
00:53:27,736 --> 00:53:29,022
(GROANING)

911
00:53:31,736 --> 00:53:32,737
(GROANING)

912
00:53:36,296 --> 00:53:38,344
Hank wants you outside
for target practice.

913
00:53:38,456 --> 00:53:40,696
HANK: <i>The suit has no weapons,
so I made you these discs.</i>

914
00:53:40,896 --> 00:53:42,136
<i>Red shrinks.</i>

915
00:53:43,176 --> 00:53:44,746
<i>Blue enlarges.</i>

916
00:53:46,656 --> 00:53:49,262
HOPE: Solenopsis mandibularis.

917
00:53:49,336 --> 00:53:50,667
HANK: <i>Known for their bite,</i>

918
00:53:50,736 --> 00:53:53,467
<i>the fire ants have evolved
into remarkable architects.</i>

919
00:53:53,536 --> 00:53:56,619
<i>They are handy to get you in and out
of difficult places.</i>

920
00:54:06,176 --> 00:54:07,940
You can do it, Scott. Come on.

921
00:54:10,576 --> 00:54:12,658
(HUFFS) They're not listening to me.

922
00:54:12,736 --> 00:54:15,387
You have to commit.
You have to mean it.

923
00:54:15,456 --> 00:54:17,424
No shortcuts, no lies.

924
00:54:17,576 --> 00:54:22,184
(SIGHS) Throwing insults into the mix
will not do anyone any good, Hope.

925
00:54:22,256 --> 00:54:23,781
We don't have time for coddling.

926
00:54:23,856 --> 00:54:26,018
Our focus should be on helping Scott!

927
00:54:26,096 --> 00:54:27,507
Really?

928
00:54:28,656 --> 00:54:30,260
Is that where our focus should be?

929
00:54:46,336 --> 00:54:47,701
(METAL TINKLING)

930
00:54:54,616 --> 00:54:55,742
Hope!

931
00:55:04,536 --> 00:55:07,267
I don't know why I came to you
in the first place.

932
00:55:14,056 --> 00:55:15,546
(DOOR CLOSES)

933
00:55:16,096 --> 00:55:18,383
We can't do this without her.

934
00:55:22,536 --> 00:55:23,617
Oh, God.

935
00:55:23,696 --> 00:55:25,664
You gotta lock your doors.

936
00:55:25,736 --> 00:55:28,626
I mean, really, there's some weird folks
in this neighborhood.

937
00:55:28,696 --> 00:55:30,380
Do you think this is a joke?

938
00:55:31,416 --> 00:55:33,942
Do you have any idea what
he's asking you to risk?

939
00:55:34,016 --> 00:55:35,256
You have a daughter.

940
00:55:35,336 --> 00:55:36,667
I'm doing this for her.

941
00:55:36,736 --> 00:55:39,706
You know, when my mother died,
I didn't see him for two weeks.

942
00:55:40,456 --> 00:55:41,456
He was in grief.

943
00:55:41,536 --> 00:55:42,901
Yeah, so was I, and I was seven.

944
00:55:42,976 --> 00:55:45,582
And he never came back.
Not in any way that counted.

945
00:55:46,536 --> 00:55:48,379
He just sent me off to boarding school.

946
00:55:49,696 --> 00:55:50,697
You know, I thought,

947
00:55:51,536 --> 00:55:52,901
with all that's at stake,

948
00:55:52,976 --> 00:55:56,139
just maybe we might have a chance
of making peace.

949
00:55:56,216 --> 00:55:58,139
But, even now,
he still wants to shut me out.

950
00:55:58,216 --> 00:56:01,106
He doesn't wanna shut you out.
He trusts you.

951
00:56:01,176 --> 00:56:02,541
Then why are you here?

952
00:56:02,616 --> 00:56:04,618
It proves that he loves you.

953
00:56:06,016 --> 00:56:08,303
Hope. Look at me.

954
00:56:09,576 --> 00:56:11,226
I'm expendable.

955
00:56:11,856 --> 00:56:13,301
That's why I'm here.

956
00:56:14,456 --> 00:56:16,299
You must have realized that by now.

957
00:56:17,176 --> 00:56:19,383
I mean, it's why I'm in the suit
and you're not.

958
00:56:21,256 --> 00:56:23,623
He would rather lose this fight
than lose you.

959
00:56:25,536 --> 00:56:26,583
Anyway...

960
00:56:27,896 --> 00:56:31,059
You know,
I didn't know you had a daughter

961
00:56:31,136 --> 00:56:33,377
when I called the cops on you.

962
00:56:37,416 --> 00:56:38,577
What's her name?

963
00:56:39,416 --> 00:56:40,906
Cassie.

964
00:56:41,656 --> 00:56:43,420
It's a pretty name.

965
00:56:46,816 --> 00:56:49,660
You have to clear your mind, Scott.
You have to make your thoughts precise.

966
00:56:49,736 --> 00:56:51,704
That's how it works.

967
00:56:52,856 --> 00:56:54,267
Think about Cassie.

968
00:56:54,336 --> 00:56:58,261
About how badly you want to see her.
And use that to focus.

969
00:57:06,976 --> 00:57:08,785
Open your eyes

970
00:57:08,856 --> 00:57:11,223
and just think about
what you want the ants to do.

971
00:57:34,056 --> 00:57:35,296
That's good!

972
00:57:53,176 --> 00:57:56,066
Your mother convinced me

973
00:57:56,136 --> 00:57:59,219
to let her join me on my missions.

974
00:57:59,736 --> 00:58:01,898
They called her the Wasp.

975
00:58:01,976 --> 00:58:04,217
She was born to it.

976
00:58:05,856 --> 00:58:07,824
And there's not a day that goes by

977
00:58:08,696 --> 00:58:11,700
that I don't regret having said yes.

978
00:58:16,176 --> 00:58:17,860
It was 1987.

979
00:58:18,656 --> 00:58:23,139
Separatists had hijacked
a Soviet missile silo in Kursk

980
00:58:24,696 --> 00:58:27,666
and launched an ICBM
at the United States.

981
00:58:35,056 --> 00:58:38,265
<i>The only way to the internal mechanics</i>

982
00:58:38,336 --> 00:58:40,259
<i>was through solid titanium.</i>

983
00:58:49,536 --> 00:58:54,258
<i>I knew I had to shrink between
the molecules to disarm the missile.</i>

984
00:58:54,336 --> 00:58:57,579
<i>But my regulator had sustained
too much damage.</i>

985
00:58:59,296 --> 00:59:00,741
<i>Your mother,</i>

986
00:59:00,816 --> 00:59:02,181
<i>she didn't hesitate.</i>

987
00:59:04,336 --> 00:59:05,940
Janet! No!

988
00:59:12,696 --> 00:59:15,176
She turned off her regulator

989
00:59:15,936 --> 00:59:17,665
and went subatomic

990
00:59:19,136 --> 00:59:21,264
to deactivate the bomb.

991
00:59:23,056 --> 00:59:24,865
And she was gone.

992
00:59:29,295 --> 00:59:31,423
Your mom died a hero.

993
00:59:34,095 --> 00:59:36,416
And I spent the next 10 years

994
00:59:36,535 --> 00:59:40,859
trying to learn all I could
about the quantum realm.

995
00:59:44,415 --> 00:59:46,543
You were trying to bring her back.

996
00:59:48,175 --> 00:59:51,782
But all I learned was we know nothing.

997
00:59:56,775 --> 00:59:58,618
It's not your fault.

998
01:00:00,775 --> 01:00:02,459
She made her choice.

999
01:00:07,935 --> 01:00:11,621
(VOICE BREAKING)
But why didn't you tell me that sooner?

1000
01:00:11,695 --> 01:00:14,665
I was trying to protect you.

1001
01:00:16,495 --> 01:00:18,145
I lost your mother.

1002
01:00:20,335 --> 01:00:23,020
I didn't mean to lose you, too.

1003
01:00:23,855 --> 01:00:25,220
I'm sorry.

1004
01:00:28,655 --> 01:00:29,861
This is awesome.

1005
01:00:30,935 --> 01:00:32,619
It's awesome, you know?

1006
01:00:32,695 --> 01:00:34,777
You guys are breaking down walls,
you're healing.

1007
01:00:35,855 --> 01:00:37,300
It's important.

1008
01:00:40,215 --> 01:00:41,705
I ruined the moment, didn't I?

1009
01:00:41,775 --> 01:00:43,504
Yes, you did. Yes.

1010
01:00:44,655 --> 01:00:46,578
I'm going to make some tea.

1011
01:00:52,215 --> 01:00:53,296
Nailed it!

1012
01:01:02,535 --> 01:01:04,583
That's a good boy, Ant-thony.

1013
01:01:34,095 --> 01:01:37,338
HANK: <i>The final phase of your training
will be a stealth incursion.</i>

1014
01:01:37,415 --> 01:01:38,576
SCOTT: It's freezing!

1015
01:01:38,655 --> 01:01:41,022
You couldn't make a suit
with a flannel lining?

1016
01:01:41,855 --> 01:01:44,586
You must retrieve this prototype
of a signal decoy.

1017
01:01:44,655 --> 01:01:47,386
It's a device that I invented
during my S.H.I.E.L.D. days.

1018
01:01:47,455 --> 01:01:49,139
HOPE: We need it to counteract
the transmission blockers

1019
01:01:49,215 --> 01:01:51,104
that Cross installed in the Futures vault.

1020
01:01:52,615 --> 01:01:54,105
It's currently collecting dust

1021
01:01:54,175 --> 01:01:57,304
in one of Howard Stark's old
storage facilities in upstate New York.

1022
01:01:57,375 --> 01:01:59,343
<i>Should be a piece of cake.</i>

1023
01:01:59,455 --> 01:02:01,298
You're over the target area.

1024
01:02:01,415 --> 01:02:03,702
Disengage now, Scott!

1025
01:02:03,775 --> 01:02:04,936
Squadron A, go!

1026
01:02:05,015 --> 01:02:06,346
B, go!

1027
01:02:08,695 --> 01:02:09,856
C, go!

1028
01:02:10,775 --> 01:02:13,346
All right, Ant-thony,
please don't drop me this time.

1029
01:02:14,175 --> 01:02:17,497
Oh, it feels like a big leap
from sugar cubes to this!

1030
01:02:17,575 --> 01:02:18,622
Stay calm.

1031
01:02:20,455 --> 01:02:22,344
SCOTT: Guys?
We might have a problem.

1032
01:02:22,415 --> 01:02:25,862
Hank, didn't you say
this was some old warehouse?

1033
01:02:25,935 --> 01:02:26,982
It's not!

1034
01:02:28,415 --> 01:02:30,258
<i>You son of a bitch!</i>

1035
01:02:32,655 --> 01:02:34,464
- Scott, get out of there.
- Abort!

1036
01:02:34,535 --> 01:02:35,616
<i>Abort now!</i>

1037
01:02:35,695 --> 01:02:38,426
No, it's okay.
It doesn't look like anyone's home.

1038
01:02:38,535 --> 01:02:40,583
Ant-thony, get me to the roof!

1039
01:02:41,455 --> 01:02:42,536
He's gonna lose the suit.

1040
01:02:42,615 --> 01:02:44,105
He's gonna lose his life.

1041
01:02:48,095 --> 01:02:49,096
(GRUNTS)

1042
01:02:49,935 --> 01:02:52,063
<i>All right, I'm on the roof
of the target building.</i>

1043
01:02:53,295 --> 01:02:54,785
Somebody's home, Scott.

1044
01:02:57,935 --> 01:02:59,266
MAN:
<i>What's going on down there, Sam?</i>

1045
01:02:59,335 --> 01:03:00,461
SCOTT: It's the Falcon!

1046
01:03:01,135 --> 01:03:03,263
I had a sensor trip
but I'm not seeing anything.

1047
01:03:03,815 --> 01:03:04,816
Wait a second.

1048
01:03:04,935 --> 01:03:06,903
HANK: Abort, Scott! Abort now!

1049
01:03:06,975 --> 01:03:08,500
It's okay. He can't see me.

1050
01:03:08,575 --> 01:03:09,622
I can see you.

1051
01:03:09,695 --> 01:03:10,856
He can see me.

1052
01:03:13,215 --> 01:03:15,138
Hi. I'm Scott.

1053
01:03:15,215 --> 01:03:16,865
Did he just say, "Hi, I'm Scott"?

1054
01:03:16,935 --> 01:03:20,223
- What are you doing here?
- First off, I'm a big fan.

1055
01:03:20,295 --> 01:03:21,945
Appreciate it. So, who the hell are you?

1056
01:03:22,775 --> 01:03:23,936
I'm Ant-Man.

1057
01:03:24,015 --> 01:03:25,255
"Ant-Man"?

1058
01:03:25,375 --> 01:03:27,457
What? You haven't heard of me?

1059
01:03:27,535 --> 01:03:29,299
No, you wouldn't have heard of me.

1060
01:03:29,695 --> 01:03:31,140
You wanna tell me what you want?

1061
01:03:31,255 --> 01:03:33,656
I was hoping I could grab
a piece of technology.

1062
01:03:33,735 --> 01:03:35,464
Just for a few days. I'm gonna return it.

1063
01:03:35,535 --> 01:03:38,186
I need it to save the world.
You know how that is.

1064
01:03:38,255 --> 01:03:39,666
I know exactly how that is.

1065
01:03:40,575 --> 01:03:41,622
Located the breach.

1066
01:03:41,695 --> 01:03:43,175
- Bringing him in.
- Sorry about this!

1067
01:03:47,655 --> 01:03:49,180
What the hell are you doing?

1068
01:03:52,135 --> 01:03:54,855
FALCON: Breach is an adult male,
who has some sort of shrinking tech.

1069
01:04:08,015 --> 01:04:09,221
SCOTT: Sorry!

1070
01:04:09,335 --> 01:04:10,825
Look, I'm sorry about this. Sorry.

1071
01:04:11,575 --> 01:04:12,576
That's enough!

1072
01:04:34,375 --> 01:04:35,456
(GROANING)

1073
01:04:35,615 --> 01:04:37,299
Ant-thony! A little help!

1074
01:04:49,935 --> 01:04:51,061
I've lost visual.

1075
01:04:56,895 --> 01:04:58,260
(GRUNTING)

1076
01:05:00,335 --> 01:05:01,575
He's inside my pack!

1077
01:05:01,655 --> 01:05:02,702
Sorry!

1078
01:05:04,295 --> 01:05:05,615
You seem like a really great guy.

1079
01:05:15,135 --> 01:05:16,705
(GRUNTING)

1080
01:05:30,655 --> 01:05:34,455
It's really important to me
that Cap never finds out about this.

1081
01:05:37,735 --> 01:05:41,262
That was completely irresponsible
and dangerous!

1082
01:05:41,935 --> 01:05:44,176
You jeopardized everything!

1083
01:06:00,135 --> 01:06:01,739
You got it.

1084
01:06:04,735 --> 01:06:05,736
Well done.

1085
01:06:05,815 --> 01:06:06,815
SCOTT: Wait a minute.

1086
01:06:06,855 --> 01:06:08,266
Did you just compliment me?

1087
01:06:08,335 --> 01:06:10,815
- He did, didn't he?
- Kind of sounded like he did.

1088
01:06:11,295 --> 01:06:12,785
(BEEPING SOFTLY)

1089
01:06:12,855 --> 01:06:14,141
I was good, wasn't I?

1090
01:06:14,335 --> 01:06:15,621
(SCOFFS)

1091
01:06:15,695 --> 01:06:19,336
Hey, how about the fact that
I fought an Avenger and didn't die?

1092
01:06:19,415 --> 01:06:21,895
Let us not dwell on the past.

1093
01:06:21,975 --> 01:06:24,103
We gotta finish our planning.

1094
01:06:26,454 --> 01:06:28,138
HOPE: Don't mind him.

1095
01:06:28,654 --> 01:06:29,655
You did good.

1096
01:06:36,534 --> 01:06:37,820
Darren.

1097
01:06:40,814 --> 01:06:42,464
How the hell did you get in here?

1098
01:06:43,694 --> 01:06:45,935
You left the front door open, Hank.

1099
01:06:46,334 --> 01:06:47,334
It's official.

1100
01:06:47,374 --> 01:06:48,535
You're old.

1101
01:06:49,094 --> 01:06:50,255
The plans.

1102
01:06:51,654 --> 01:06:53,258
He will kill him.

1103
01:06:56,494 --> 01:06:59,179
Well, to what do I owe this pleasure?

1104
01:07:00,214 --> 01:07:01,704
I have good news.

1105
01:07:01,774 --> 01:07:03,014
Really?

1106
01:07:03,854 --> 01:07:04,855
What's that?

1107
01:07:05,454 --> 01:07:10,096
Pym Tech, the company you created,

1108
01:07:10,174 --> 01:07:13,974
is about to become one of the most
profitable operations in the world.

1109
01:07:14,054 --> 01:07:17,820
We're anticipating $15 billion in sales,
tomorrow alone.

1110
01:07:24,414 --> 01:07:25,540
You're welcome.

1111
01:07:29,894 --> 01:07:32,374
I know this is odd,
but I'd like you to be there.

1112
01:07:33,054 --> 01:07:35,056
This is my moment.
I want you to see it.

1113
01:07:36,294 --> 01:07:37,864
Sure, Darren. Yeah, sure.

1114
01:07:37,934 --> 01:07:39,220
I'll be there.

1115
01:07:56,294 --> 01:07:57,739
What did you see in me?

1116
01:07:58,934 --> 01:08:00,345
I don't know what you mean.

1117
01:08:01,254 --> 01:08:03,860
All those years ago, you picked me.

1118
01:08:03,934 --> 01:08:05,424
What did you see?

1119
01:08:07,614 --> 01:08:09,378
I saw myself.

1120
01:08:09,974 --> 01:08:12,375
Then why did you push me away?

1121
01:08:13,934 --> 01:08:17,256
Because I saw too much of myself.

1122
01:08:28,134 --> 01:08:29,545
HOPE: <i>He knows. He's baiting you.</i>

1123
01:08:29,614 --> 01:08:31,343
We have to call it off.

1124
01:08:31,414 --> 01:08:32,575
We're all taking risks.

1125
01:08:32,654 --> 01:08:33,985
What if he saw me here?

1126
01:08:34,054 --> 01:08:35,385
He didn't. There's no way.

1127
01:08:35,454 --> 01:08:37,821
- How do you know that?
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)

1128
01:08:45,294 --> 01:08:46,580
Darren, hi.

1129
01:08:46,694 --> 01:08:49,504
Hope, where are you right now?

1130
01:08:50,134 --> 01:08:51,340
I'm at home. Why?

1131
01:08:51,414 --> 01:08:53,178
<i>I just saw Hank.</i>

1132
01:08:53,254 --> 01:08:55,063
<i>I still get nothing but contempt from him.</i>

1133
01:08:55,134 --> 01:08:58,695
Don't let him rile you up.
He's just a senile old man.

1134
01:08:58,774 --> 01:09:01,220
<i>We need to start everyone working
around the clock.</i>

1135
01:09:01,334 --> 01:09:03,143
<i>Get the assembly line up and running.</i>

1136
01:09:03,214 --> 01:09:04,500
<i>And I'm tripling security.</i>

1137
01:09:04,574 --> 01:09:06,576
Full sensors at all entrances

1138
01:09:06,654 --> 01:09:10,056
and exterior air vents
fitted with steel micro-mesh.

1139
01:09:10,174 --> 01:09:11,778
Great. Good idea.

1140
01:09:11,854 --> 01:09:16,178
<i>Thank you, Hope.
I'm so lucky to have you on my team.</i>

1141
01:09:18,614 --> 01:09:23,097
He's tripling security.
He's lost his mind, and he's onto you.

1142
01:09:23,174 --> 01:09:25,142
But he is not onto you.

1143
01:09:25,214 --> 01:09:27,581
He's adding full body scanners
to all entrances

1144
01:09:27,694 --> 01:09:29,423
and closing exterior vents.

1145
01:09:29,494 --> 01:09:31,417
How are we gonna get Scott inside?

1146
01:09:32,934 --> 01:09:34,459
The water main.

1147
01:09:35,574 --> 01:09:37,497
You can't add security to a water main.

1148
01:09:37,574 --> 01:09:39,895
The pressure is too strong,
but if we can decrease it,

1149
01:09:39,974 --> 01:09:41,180
that's how I get in.

1150
01:09:41,254 --> 01:09:43,461
Somebody would have to reach
the building's control center

1151
01:09:43,534 --> 01:09:44,899
to change the water pressure.

1152
01:09:44,974 --> 01:09:47,705
Hank and I will be beside Cross.
How are we supposed to do that?

1153
01:09:47,774 --> 01:09:49,299
So we expand our team.

1154
01:09:49,894 --> 01:09:50,895
What do we need?

1155
01:09:50,974 --> 01:09:54,376
A fake security guard on the inside
to de-pressurize the water system,

1156
01:09:54,454 --> 01:09:56,297
somebody else to hack in
to the power supply

1157
01:09:56,374 --> 01:09:57,785
and kill the laser grid,

1158
01:09:57,854 --> 01:10:00,175
and a getaway guy.

1159
01:10:00,254 --> 01:10:04,225
No, no. No, no, no.
Not those three Wombats. No way.

1160
01:10:04,854 --> 01:10:06,299
LUIS: Thank you for the coffee, ma'am.

1161
01:10:06,374 --> 01:10:09,981
It's not too often that you rob a place
and then get welcomed back.

1162
01:10:10,054 --> 01:10:11,943
(CHUCKLES)
Because we just robbed you.

1163
01:10:13,494 --> 01:10:17,055
You know that he was arrested
for stealing a smoothie machine, right?

1164
01:10:17,134 --> 01:10:18,420
Two smoothie machines.

1165
01:10:18,534 --> 01:10:20,104
Are you sure they can handle this?

1166
01:10:20,174 --> 01:10:21,585
Oh, we can handle it.
We're professionals.

1167
01:10:21,654 --> 01:10:25,261
You'll forgive us if we're not
instilled with confidence.

1168
01:10:25,374 --> 01:10:28,025
Well, hey, everybody just kick back
and relax a little bit, man.

1169
01:10:28,094 --> 01:10:29,425
We know our business.

1170
01:10:29,494 --> 01:10:31,861
We broke into this spooky-ass house,
didn't we?

1171
01:10:31,934 --> 01:10:33,379
I let you.

1172
01:10:33,454 --> 01:10:36,742
Well, one could say that
I let you let me.

1173
01:10:36,814 --> 01:10:40,136
- Look, it's okay. They can handle this.
- Yeah, we can handle it.

1174
01:10:40,214 --> 01:10:41,978
- SCOTT: You got their credentials?
- He's in the system.

1175
01:10:42,054 --> 01:10:44,534
- I'm in the system?
- You're in the system.

1176
01:10:44,614 --> 01:10:45,820
The system?

1177
01:10:45,894 --> 01:10:48,181
Yeah, we're doomed.

1178
01:10:48,254 --> 01:10:49,301
SCOTT: All right.

1179
01:10:49,374 --> 01:10:51,058
There's something
you guys need to see.

1180
01:10:51,134 --> 01:10:52,977
When you get to this corner,

1181
01:10:53,054 --> 01:10:55,819
there's gonna be three offices
on your left side.

1182
01:10:55,894 --> 01:10:57,225
DAVE: Damn!

1183
01:10:58,894 --> 01:11:01,625
Whoa! That's so cool, bro!

1184
01:11:01,694 --> 01:11:04,379
Now, look,
this is gonna get weird, all right?

1185
01:11:04,454 --> 01:11:07,697
It's pretty freaky, but it's safe.
There's no reason to be scared.

1186
01:11:07,774 --> 01:11:09,105
Oh, no, no. Daddy don't get scared.

1187
01:11:09,174 --> 01:11:11,017
- Really?
- Yeah.

1188
01:11:11,094 --> 01:11:12,255
Good.

1189
01:11:16,214 --> 01:11:17,545
(GASPS)

1190
01:11:19,414 --> 01:11:21,337
This is the work of gypsies.

1191
01:11:21,414 --> 01:11:22,540
DAVE: (STAMMERING)
That's witchcraft.

1192
01:11:22,614 --> 01:11:23,775
Wow, that's amazing.

1193
01:11:24,414 --> 01:11:25,904
That's like some David Copperfield shit.

1194
01:11:25,974 --> 01:11:27,055
DAVE: That's some kind of wizardry.

1195
01:11:27,134 --> 01:11:28,215
KURT: This is sorcery!

1196
01:11:28,294 --> 01:11:29,420
How'd you do that, bro?

1197
01:11:29,494 --> 01:11:31,462
SCOTT: Don't freak out.
Look at your shoulder.

1198
01:11:31,974 --> 01:11:33,260
Ahhh!

1199
01:11:33,334 --> 01:11:34,779
Get off! Get off!

1200
01:11:34,854 --> 01:11:37,380
SCOTT: Wait, I thought
Daddy didn't get scared!

1201
01:11:37,454 --> 01:11:38,660
(SNORING)

1202
01:11:39,654 --> 01:11:41,065
I gave them each half a Xanax

1203
01:11:41,134 --> 01:11:43,740
and Hank explained the science
of the suit to them.

1204
01:11:43,814 --> 01:11:45,976
They fell right asleep.

1205
01:11:46,654 --> 01:11:49,225
Hey, look, I wanna thank you for...

1206
01:11:49,334 --> 01:11:51,257
No, please don't.

1207
01:11:51,334 --> 01:11:53,780
We're all doing this for reasons
much bigger than any one of us.

1208
01:11:53,854 --> 01:11:57,700
I'm just glad that you might have
a slight chance of maybe pulling this off.

1209
01:11:57,774 --> 01:12:00,857
Hey, thank you, you know,
for that pep talk.

1210
01:12:00,934 --> 01:12:03,619
You know, the honest truth is,
I actually went from despising you

1211
01:12:03,694 --> 01:12:05,298
to almost liking you.

1212
01:12:05,374 --> 01:12:07,103
You really should write poetry.

1213
01:12:07,174 --> 01:12:08,585
(CHUCKLES)

1214
01:12:10,454 --> 01:12:12,183
Get some sleep, Scott.

1215
01:12:35,574 --> 01:12:36,905
(SOFT WHIRRING)

1216
01:13:02,694 --> 01:13:05,504
All right, just so we're clear,
everyone here knows their role, right?

1217
01:13:05,574 --> 01:13:07,178
- Dave?
- Wheels on the ground.

1218
01:13:07,254 --> 01:13:08,585
- Kurt?
- Eyes in the sky.

1219
01:13:08,654 --> 01:13:10,099
- Luis?
- Oh, man, you know it.

1220
01:13:10,174 --> 01:13:11,694
You know what?
I get to wear a uniform.

1221
01:13:11,734 --> 01:13:13,338
- That's what's up.
- Luis.

1222
01:13:13,414 --> 01:13:15,621
I'm sorry. I'm good. I'm good.
I'm just excited.

1223
01:13:15,694 --> 01:13:17,025
Plus, your girlfriend's really hot.

1224
01:13:17,094 --> 01:13:18,425
So, you know,
that makes me nervous, too.

1225
01:13:18,494 --> 01:13:19,495
And you are very beautiful, ma'am.

1226
01:13:19,574 --> 01:13:21,463
- Oh, my Lord.
- She's not my...

1227
01:13:21,534 --> 01:13:23,821
You know what? I was thinking of
a tactic, like when I go undercover.

1228
01:13:23,894 --> 01:13:25,816
Like a whistling. You know
what I'm saying? To like, blend in.

1229
01:13:25,893 --> 01:13:28,976
No. Don't whistle. No whistling.

1230
01:13:29,053 --> 01:13:31,101
It's not <i>The Andy Griffith</i> Show.
No whistling.

1231
01:13:48,853 --> 01:13:50,139
All clear in Sector One.

1232
01:13:55,293 --> 01:13:56,454
GUARD: Step out.

1233
01:13:59,053 --> 01:14:00,259
All clear.

1234
01:14:05,933 --> 01:14:07,059
We're set.

1235
01:14:07,613 --> 01:14:08,978
Wish me luck.

1236
01:14:20,333 --> 01:14:22,097
Utilities online.

1237
01:14:22,173 --> 01:14:24,460
(WHISTLING <i>IT'S A SMALL WORLD</i>)

1238
01:14:34,533 --> 01:14:36,342
Hey! What are you doing?

1239
01:14:36,893 --> 01:14:41,501
Uh... Boss-man said to secure the area,
so I'm securing it.

1240
01:14:42,893 --> 01:14:44,224
I'm the boss.

1241
01:14:44,493 --> 01:14:45,983
- Oh.
- Utilities 1.3...

1242
01:14:52,053 --> 01:14:53,657
(WATER FLOWING)

1243
01:14:56,093 --> 01:14:57,538
(BEEPING)

1244
01:15:00,133 --> 01:15:02,215
KURT: <i>Water level is dropping!</i>

1245
01:15:21,213 --> 01:15:22,419
(YELPS)

1246
01:15:30,733 --> 01:15:32,576
KURT: <i>Coming up on extraction pipe.</i>

1247
01:15:32,653 --> 01:15:34,064
SCOTT: All right, I see it.

1248
01:15:42,213 --> 01:15:45,535
All right, come on, I gotta get up there.
That's it. That's it, guys! Yes!

1249
01:15:48,653 --> 01:15:51,782
Yes! You got it! You got it! Come on!

1250
01:15:54,413 --> 01:15:55,539
(TAPPING)

1251
01:15:56,253 --> 01:15:58,574
- All right, let's fly, Ant-thony.
- (CHITTERING)

1252
01:16:08,973 --> 01:16:11,055
The Ant-Man is in the building.

1253
01:16:11,133 --> 01:16:14,057
DAVE: Pym's pulling up. Right on time.

1254
01:16:16,093 --> 01:16:18,141
Got a Crown Vic right outside there.

1255
01:16:18,213 --> 01:16:19,419
This is problem?

1256
01:16:19,493 --> 01:16:21,541
DAVE: Considering the Crown Vic's
the most commonly used car

1257
01:16:21,613 --> 01:16:22,774
for undercover cops, man,

1258
01:16:23,533 --> 01:16:24,944
yes, this is problem.

1259
01:16:28,773 --> 01:16:29,934
That's Pym.

1260
01:16:32,653 --> 01:16:34,018
DAVE: Oh, no.

1261
01:16:34,093 --> 01:16:35,333
SCOTT: I'm deploying the bullet ants.

1262
01:16:35,453 --> 01:16:36,978
<i>Papanera Claire de Merna Merna...</i>

1263
01:16:37,053 --> 01:16:39,977
<i>I don't remember what it's called,
but I feel bad for this guy.</i>

1264
01:16:41,293 --> 01:16:42,419
- What's up, man?
- Hey.

1265
01:16:48,253 --> 01:16:49,698
Ow! Ow!

1266
01:16:52,453 --> 01:16:53,579
See? That's what I'm talking about.

1267
01:16:53,653 --> 01:16:56,054
That's what I call
an unfortunate casualty

1268
01:16:56,133 --> 01:16:58,135
in a very serious operation.

1269
01:17:07,373 --> 01:17:09,501
KURT: Signal decoy in place.

1270
01:17:10,053 --> 01:17:11,976
Mean, pretty lady did good, Scott.

1271
01:17:13,213 --> 01:17:15,500
DAVE: (SCOFFS)
Looks like Pym's getting arrested.

1272
01:17:15,573 --> 01:17:17,257
Scott, we have problem.

1273
01:17:17,333 --> 01:17:19,256
SCOTT: <i>Problem? What's the problem?</i>

1274
01:17:20,093 --> 01:17:22,573
Dave! Dave, that's not part of plan!

1275
01:17:22,653 --> 01:17:24,303
Listen to me.

1276
01:17:24,373 --> 01:17:28,173
If I don't get into this building,
people will die.

1277
01:17:28,813 --> 01:17:30,542
That's awfully dramatic.

1278
01:17:30,613 --> 01:17:32,183
(SIREN BLARING)

1279
01:17:33,413 --> 01:17:34,699
Are you kidding me?

1280
01:17:36,333 --> 01:17:38,176
- (TIRES SQUEALING)
- (DAVE LAUGHING)

1281
01:17:39,173 --> 01:17:40,937
Problem solved.

1282
01:17:55,853 --> 01:17:57,059
Well...

1283
01:17:58,853 --> 01:18:00,696
How do I look?

1284
01:18:09,973 --> 01:18:10,974
There he is.

1285
01:18:12,613 --> 01:18:15,776
Just in time. Come on.

1286
01:18:25,093 --> 01:18:26,982
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE:
<i>12-point verification.</i>

1287
01:18:27,053 --> 01:18:28,862
Little over-the-top,
don't you think, Darren?

1288
01:18:28,933 --> 01:18:30,458
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE:
<i>Confirming authorization level.</i>

1289
01:18:30,533 --> 01:18:32,137
Well, you can never be too safe.

1290
01:18:32,213 --> 01:18:33,733
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE:
<i>Access granted.</i>

1291
01:18:40,933 --> 01:18:42,423
HANK: Gotta hand it to you, Darren.

1292
01:18:43,093 --> 01:18:45,061
You really did it.

1293
01:18:45,133 --> 01:18:46,976
And you only know the half of it, Hank.

1294
01:18:48,653 --> 01:18:50,576
(AUTOMATIC LOCKS CLICKING)

1295
01:19:13,173 --> 01:19:14,823
Arriving in second position.

1296
01:19:16,733 --> 01:19:18,781
All right, top speed, Ant-thony. Let's go!

1297
01:19:29,773 --> 01:19:31,059
Proceeding to command position.

1298
01:19:48,853 --> 01:19:50,457
I'll be right back, Ant-thony.

1299
01:19:52,373 --> 01:19:54,455
All right, guys. I'm in position.

1300
01:19:54,533 --> 01:19:56,217
I'm gonna signal the ants.

1301
01:19:56,293 --> 01:19:58,580
PAXTON: No, no, no, no, no!

1302
01:19:58,813 --> 01:19:59,814
(GRUNTS)

1303
01:19:59,893 --> 01:20:01,019
DAVE: Did you see that?

1304
01:20:01,093 --> 01:20:02,094
(LAUGHING)

1305
01:20:02,173 --> 01:20:03,857
(MUSICAL CAR HORN HONKING)

1306
01:20:07,493 --> 01:20:09,063
Assume formation.

1307
01:20:09,133 --> 01:20:11,056
All right, you cute little crazies,

1308
01:20:11,133 --> 01:20:12,862
let's fry these servers!

1309
01:20:17,693 --> 01:20:19,263
(POWERING DOWN)

1310
01:20:22,333 --> 01:20:23,982
(GRUNTS)

1311
01:20:25,092 --> 01:20:27,174
Let's go get 'em, buddy!

1312
01:20:37,012 --> 01:20:38,502
(WHOOPING)

1313
01:20:39,692 --> 01:20:40,693
KURT: <i>Servers are fried.</i>

1314
01:20:40,772 --> 01:20:42,979
Data backup completely erased.

1315
01:20:43,052 --> 01:20:44,656
SCOTT:
Heading to the particle chamber.

1316
01:20:51,172 --> 01:20:53,015
Hello, Dr. Cross.

1317
01:20:56,972 --> 01:20:59,373
My associates have agreed
to your terms.

1318
01:20:59,452 --> 01:21:00,613
Wonderful.

1319
01:21:00,692 --> 01:21:03,536
Mr. Carson introduced me
to these fine gentlemen here.

1320
01:21:03,612 --> 01:21:05,216
They're representatives of Hydra.

1321
01:21:05,292 --> 01:21:06,623
They're not what they were.

1322
01:21:06,692 --> 01:21:08,979
They're doing some interesting work.

1323
01:21:09,052 --> 01:21:11,498
(CHUCKLING) And I'm enjoying myself.

1324
01:21:12,252 --> 01:21:14,414
You tried to hide
your technology from me.

1325
01:21:14,492 --> 01:21:16,460
And now it's gonna blow up in your face.

1326
01:21:16,532 --> 01:21:17,772
(GRUNTS)

1327
01:21:20,372 --> 01:21:21,419
Wow.

1328
01:21:22,092 --> 01:21:25,813
Wow! I mean, I saw that punch coming
a mile away,

1329
01:21:25,892 --> 01:21:27,974
but I just figured it'd
be all pathetic and weak.

1330
01:21:28,052 --> 01:21:29,577
Well, you figured wrong.

1331
01:21:30,772 --> 01:21:32,103
PAXTON: I know this van.

1332
01:21:33,532 --> 01:21:34,693
Anybody home?

1333
01:21:34,772 --> 01:21:36,422
(BOTH SHUSHING)

1334
01:21:40,372 --> 01:21:41,533
All right, guys. I'm here.

1335
01:21:46,132 --> 01:21:47,941
I'm setting the charges.

1336
01:22:06,612 --> 01:22:09,821
Great job, guys.
I'll take it from here.

1337
01:22:18,932 --> 01:22:21,538
Good boy, Ant-thony.

1338
01:22:22,492 --> 01:22:23,493
Final position.

1339
01:22:32,132 --> 01:22:34,419
Guys, how we looking on that laser grid?

1340
01:22:34,492 --> 01:22:36,062
KURT: Almost.
DAVE: No, you're not.

1341
01:22:36,132 --> 01:22:37,612
- I'm getting close!
- No, you're not.

1342
01:22:42,212 --> 01:22:43,896
- (BANGING ON DOOR)
- PAXTON: San Francisco P.D.!

1343
01:22:43,972 --> 01:22:44,973
Out of the van!

1344
01:22:45,612 --> 01:22:46,612
I know you're in there!

1345
01:22:46,652 --> 01:22:48,814
- Make it go faster.
- Dude, seriously.

1346
01:22:50,932 --> 01:22:51,933
(BANGING CONTINUES)

1347
01:22:54,532 --> 01:22:56,614
Ready to jump.
Do you read, Kurt?

1348
01:22:56,692 --> 01:22:57,693
So close.

1349
01:22:58,492 --> 01:22:59,903
- Okay, hold up! Wait a minute!
- Freeze!

1350
01:22:59,972 --> 01:23:01,622
There was a black guy
that looked exactly like me

1351
01:23:01,692 --> 01:23:03,615
who attacked us and put us
in the back of this disgusting van.

1352
01:23:03,692 --> 01:23:05,182
- Get out of the van!
- DAVE: Okay, I'm coming.

1353
01:23:05,252 --> 01:23:07,061
Take it easy!

1354
01:23:07,132 --> 01:23:09,100
KURT: No, I will not move! Go now!

1355
01:23:11,252 --> 01:23:13,300
- Wait!
- What? What do you mean, "Wait"?

1356
01:23:20,212 --> 01:23:21,213
Phew!

1357
01:23:23,852 --> 01:23:24,853
What? What?

1358
01:23:26,492 --> 01:23:27,778
DARREN: Hey, little guy.

1359
01:23:29,572 --> 01:23:30,983
(LAUGHING)

1360
01:23:36,652 --> 01:23:37,813
(GROANS)

1361
01:23:40,492 --> 01:23:43,621
I always suspected you had
a suit stored away somewhere.

1362
01:23:43,692 --> 01:23:44,692
Which begs the question,

1363
01:23:44,732 --> 01:23:46,894
who is the new Ant-Man?

1364
01:23:46,972 --> 01:23:49,418
Who is the man that my beloved mentor

1365
01:23:49,492 --> 01:23:51,381
trusted even more than me?

1366
01:23:53,612 --> 01:23:55,899
Scott Lang.

1367
01:23:57,132 --> 01:23:58,702
A martyr

1368
01:23:58,812 --> 01:24:01,258
who took on the system
and paid the price,

1369
01:24:01,332 --> 01:24:04,939
losing his family and his only daughter
in the process.

1370
01:24:05,012 --> 01:24:08,255
Exactly your kind of guy, Hank!

1371
01:24:09,252 --> 01:24:14,053
He escapes his jail cell
without leaving any clue as to how.

1372
01:24:14,772 --> 01:24:18,219
- (BEEPS)
- And then he disappears magically,

1373
01:24:19,412 --> 01:24:21,540
despite having no money to his name.

1374
01:24:21,612 --> 01:24:24,297
And now he brings me the Ant-Man suit.

1375
01:24:26,652 --> 01:24:30,418
The only thing that can rival my creation.

1376
01:24:30,492 --> 01:24:33,894
Darren, don't do this.

1377
01:24:34,012 --> 01:24:36,060
If you sell to these men,

1378
01:24:36,132 --> 01:24:37,577
it's gonna be chaos.

1379
01:24:37,652 --> 01:24:39,063
I already have.

1380
01:24:39,132 --> 01:24:40,577
And for twice the price,

1381
01:24:40,652 --> 01:24:42,654
thanks to you.

1382
01:24:42,772 --> 01:24:46,140
It's not easy to successfully infiltrate
an Avengers facility.

1383
01:24:46,212 --> 01:24:48,180
Thankfully, word travels fast.

1384
01:24:48,252 --> 01:24:52,098
I'll sell them the Yellowjacket,
but I'm keeping the particle to myself.

1385
01:24:53,132 --> 01:24:54,543
They don't run on diesel.

1386
01:24:54,612 --> 01:24:57,502
If you want the fuel,
you'll have to come to me.

1387
01:24:58,652 --> 01:25:00,461
What do you call the only man

1388
01:25:00,532 --> 01:25:03,502
who can arm the most
powerful weapon in the world?

1389
01:25:04,132 --> 01:25:06,783
The most powerful man in the world.

1390
01:25:06,852 --> 01:25:08,377
You proud of me yet?

1391
01:25:08,452 --> 01:25:11,501
You can stop this, Darren.
It's not too late.

1392
01:25:11,572 --> 01:25:15,293
It's been too late for a long time now.

1393
01:25:16,252 --> 01:25:18,300
Darren!

1394
01:25:19,452 --> 01:25:20,533
What are you doing?

1395
01:25:20,612 --> 01:25:23,821
He wasn't any more capable of
caring for you than he was for me.

1396
01:25:23,892 --> 01:25:25,621
This is not who you are.

1397
01:25:25,732 --> 01:25:28,542
It's the particles altering
your brain chemistry.

1398
01:25:36,892 --> 01:25:38,940
Wait! Wait, wait, wait, wait.

1399
01:25:39,012 --> 01:25:40,059
(SIGHS)

1400
01:25:40,652 --> 01:25:43,337
You're right.
I have to be the one to do it.

1401
01:25:45,932 --> 01:25:47,218
Here we go.

1402
01:25:48,612 --> 01:25:51,821
Drop your gun.

1403
01:25:54,412 --> 01:25:57,382
You know, I came to the house
the other night to kill him,

1404
01:25:57,452 --> 01:25:58,533
but you were there.

1405
01:25:58,612 --> 01:26:02,139
You're sick and I can help you.
Just put the gun down.

1406
01:26:02,212 --> 01:26:03,492
I wasn't ready to kill you then,

1407
01:26:05,252 --> 01:26:06,458
but I think I am now!

1408
01:26:06,532 --> 01:26:08,614
Drop your gun now!

1409
01:26:08,732 --> 01:26:12,100
You picked the wrong side, Hope.

1410
01:26:24,332 --> 01:26:26,334
- (GROANS)
- Dad!

1411
01:26:33,492 --> 01:26:34,698
(GROANING)

1412
01:26:35,052 --> 01:26:36,292
SCOTT: Hank, no.

1413
01:26:36,372 --> 01:26:38,022
No, Hank.

1414
01:26:38,612 --> 01:26:40,580
Hank? Listen, you're gonna be okay.

1415
01:26:40,652 --> 01:26:42,732
- All right? You're gonna be just fine.
- (GUN COCKS)

1416
01:26:43,692 --> 01:26:46,616
Take the suit off,
or I'll blow your brains out and peel it off.

1417
01:26:49,492 --> 01:26:50,698
(GUN CLICKING)

1418
01:27:07,732 --> 01:27:09,257
(YELPING)

1419
01:27:11,252 --> 01:27:12,378
(ALARM BLARING)

1420
01:27:12,452 --> 01:27:14,341
We got a 10-33 at Pym Tech.

1421
01:27:14,412 --> 01:27:15,902
Request immediate backup!

1422
01:27:15,972 --> 01:27:17,258
DAVE: Go, go, go!

1423
01:27:25,411 --> 01:27:26,572
(GASPS)

1424
01:27:30,171 --> 01:27:32,060
Get me to the roof.

1425
01:27:32,131 --> 01:27:33,371
And radio ahead.

1426
01:27:33,451 --> 01:27:36,295
I want to make sure the helicopter
is ready to take off.

1427
01:27:36,371 --> 01:27:37,418
You two,

1428
01:27:37,491 --> 01:27:40,176
kill anything that comes out of that vault!

1429
01:27:40,251 --> 01:27:43,460
Dad, can you move?

1430
01:27:45,811 --> 01:27:47,222
We need to get him out of here.

1431
01:27:48,531 --> 01:27:51,137
Go get that suit.

1432
01:28:34,451 --> 01:28:35,532
Hey, Scotty.

1433
01:28:35,611 --> 01:28:37,340
Hey, did I save your life?

1434
01:28:38,491 --> 01:28:41,097
Scotty?

1435
01:28:41,371 --> 01:28:42,736
(PANTING)

1436
01:28:43,491 --> 01:28:45,095
Thank you, Luis.

1437
01:28:45,171 --> 01:28:46,741
- Are we the good guys?
- Yeah.

1438
01:28:46,811 --> 01:28:49,092
- We're the good guys, right?
- Yeah, we're the good guys.

1439
01:28:49,611 --> 01:28:51,375
Feels kinda weird, you know.

1440
01:28:51,451 --> 01:28:53,533
Yeah, but we're not done yet.

1441
01:28:53,611 --> 01:28:55,693
Get out of here before this place blows!

1442
01:29:02,371 --> 01:29:05,659
(GROANS) Damn it! That guy.

1443
01:29:06,811 --> 01:29:08,939
Hey! We're getting out of here!

1444
01:29:09,171 --> 01:29:10,502
(GROANING)

1445
01:29:13,451 --> 01:29:14,498
HOPE: The charges are set.

1446
01:29:14,571 --> 01:29:16,573
We've gotta find a way out of here.
And fast.

1447
01:29:16,651 --> 01:29:18,574
Don't worry.

1448
01:29:18,651 --> 01:29:21,222
I'm not gonna die.

1449
01:29:21,291 --> 01:29:22,736
And neither are you.

1450
01:29:23,811 --> 01:29:26,337
It's not a keychain.

1451
01:29:29,411 --> 01:29:32,381
It's total chaos in here!
Multiple shots fired!

1452
01:29:43,171 --> 01:29:44,935
And there's a tank.

1453
01:29:54,491 --> 01:29:56,061
A little help!

1454
01:29:57,571 --> 01:29:58,697
I got it.

1455
01:29:59,491 --> 01:30:00,936
We need a doctor!

1456
01:30:02,251 --> 01:30:03,491
We've got him.

1457
01:30:04,331 --> 01:30:05,537
(MUSICAL CAR HORN HONKING)

1458
01:30:05,611 --> 01:30:07,261
Thank you.

1459
01:30:08,571 --> 01:30:10,175
Let's go!

1460
01:30:24,571 --> 01:30:25,936
(ANT-THONY SHRIEKING)

1461
01:30:26,251 --> 01:30:27,616
Ant-thony!

1462
01:30:40,931 --> 01:30:42,217
Go!

1463
01:30:43,491 --> 01:30:44,771
SCOTT: You're gonna regret that.

1464
01:30:55,011 --> 01:30:56,661
Wait a minute! Get out of that van!

1465
01:30:56,771 --> 01:30:58,341
- What?
- Get out of that van!

1466
01:30:58,411 --> 01:31:00,291
It's too loud, there's a tank.
I can't hear you!

1467
01:31:01,371 --> 01:31:03,851
Hey! Hey!

1468
01:31:08,651 --> 01:31:10,938
MAN: Are you crazy? Put the gun down!

1469
01:31:11,011 --> 01:31:12,536
The windows!

1470
01:31:17,011 --> 01:31:19,855
Did you think you could
stop the future with a heist?

1471
01:31:19,931 --> 01:31:21,501
SCOTT: It was never just a heist!

1472
01:31:43,691 --> 01:31:45,181
Put the gun down!

1473
01:31:50,171 --> 01:31:51,332
(SCREAMING)

1474
01:31:53,771 --> 01:31:55,899
Okay, I got him, I got him.
There he is! Go, go, go!

1475
01:32:12,171 --> 01:32:14,219
We gotta set her down somewhere.

1476
01:32:28,491 --> 01:32:29,492
(YELLS)

1477
01:32:44,211 --> 01:32:46,578
DARREN: I'm gonna disintegrate you!

1478
01:32:46,651 --> 01:32:48,251
SIRI: <i>Playing Disintegration
by the Cure.</i>

1479
01:32:49,251 --> 01:32:51,094
(SONG PLAYING LOUDLY)

1480
01:33:23,571 --> 01:33:24,777
(GIRL SCREAMS)

1481
01:33:26,851 --> 01:33:27,932
Call 911!

1482
01:33:28,091 --> 01:33:29,138
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

1483
01:33:36,931 --> 01:33:38,012
(GROANS)

1484
01:33:41,411 --> 01:33:42,412
(CHITTERING)

1485
01:33:42,491 --> 01:33:43,617
(CRACKLING)

1486
01:33:46,251 --> 01:33:48,015
- SCOTT: It's okay.
- (ALL YELP)

1487
01:33:52,451 --> 01:33:54,419
Freeze! Put your hands up!
Get them up!

1488
01:33:56,971 --> 01:33:57,972
Scott?

1489
01:33:58,051 --> 01:33:59,371
Paxton, you have to listen to me!

1490
01:33:59,771 --> 01:34:01,296
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

1491
01:34:07,731 --> 01:34:09,017
(BOTH GROAN)

1492
01:34:19,011 --> 01:34:20,376
(SCREAMING)

1493
01:34:27,650 --> 01:34:29,937
Paxton, turn around! Take me back!

1494
01:34:30,010 --> 01:34:32,012
I am taking you back. To prison.

1495
01:34:32,090 --> 01:34:34,570
There's something in that backyard
that needs to be destroyed.

1496
01:34:34,650 --> 01:34:35,731
In the bug zapper. There...

1497
01:34:36,130 --> 01:34:37,416
(TIRES SCREECH)

1498
01:34:37,530 --> 01:34:40,898
You need to desist right now!
Your delusions are out of hand.

1499
